{{More footnotes|date=March 2008}} {{Infobox person | name = Franc Miklošič | image = Franz von Miklosich (Dauthage, 1853).jpg | alt = | caption = Franc Miklošič | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1813|11|20}} | birth_place = [[Radomerščak]], [[Ljutomer]], [[Austrian Empire]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1891|03|07|1813|11|20}} | death_place = | citizenship = Austrian | nationality = Slovenian | other_names = Franz Xaver Ritter von Miklosich | occupation = philologist | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }} '''Franc Miklošič''' (also known in German as {{lang|de|'''Franz Xaver Ritter von Miklosich'''}}) (20 November 1813 – 7 March 1891) was a [[Slovenes|Slovene]] [[philology|philologist]].
==Early life== Miklošič was born in the small village of [[Radomerščak]] near the [[Lower Styria]]n town of [[Ljutomer]], then part of the [[Austrian Empire]]. He graduated from the [[University of Graz]] with a doctor of philosophy degree.
==Career== He was professor of philosophy at the University of Graz. In 1838, he went to the [[University of Vienna]], where he received the degree of doctor of law. During his studies, he became influenced by the works of the Slovenian philologist and linguist [[Jernej Kopitar]]. He abandoned law, devoting most of his later life to the study of [[Slavic languages]].
In 1844, he obtained a post at the [[Austrian National Library|Imperial Library of Vienna]], where he remained to 1862. In 1844, he published a review of [[Franz Bopp]]'s book ''Comparative Grammar,'' which attracted attention from the Viennese academic circles. This publication then launched a long series of works, in which Miklošič showed an immense erudition. His works led to a revolutionary change in the study of Slavic languages.
In 1849 Miklošič was appointed to the newly created chair of Slavic philology at the [[University of Vienna]], and he occupied it until 1886. He became a member of the [[Austrian Academy of Sciences|Academy of Vienna]], which appointed him secretary of its historical and philosophical section, a member of the council of public instruction and of the upper house, and correspondent of the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres|French Academy of Inscriptions and Humanities]]. His numerous writings deal not only with the Slavic languages, but also with [[Romanian language|Romanian]], [[Aromanian language|Aromanian]], [[Albanian language|Albanian]], [[Greek language|Greek]], and [[Romani language|Romani]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mojaslovenija.net/veliki_slovenci/veliki_slovenci_franc_miklosic.html |title=Veliki Slovenci: Franc Miklošič |language=Slovenian |trans-title=Great Slovenes: Franc Miklošič |work=Moja Slovenija [My Slovenia] |first=Tomaž |last=Štefe |year=2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110625064902/http://www.mojaslovenija.net/veliki_slovenci/veliki_slovenci_franc_miklosic.html |archivedate=2011-06-25 |df= }}</ref>
From 1872-1880, Miklošič published his original survey of Romani dialects, ''Über die Mundarten und Wanderungen der Zigeuner Europas''. This work included a discussion of their origins, migration routes, an historical-comparative grammar, and a lexicon. He identified a substantial Greek element that was shared by the Romani dialects, and thus named a "Greek-speaking area" as the "European homeland of the Gypsies".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://romani.humanities.manchester.ac.uk/whatis/linguistics/history.shtml |title=ROMANI Project - Manchester |publisher=Romani.humanities.manchester.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-10-05}}</ref>
==Political engagement== In the [[Revolutions of 1848|Spring of Nations]] of 1848, Miklošič, who was 35 at the time, actively engaged in the [[Slovene national movement]]. He was the chairman of the political association, called ''Slovenija'' (Slovenia) organized by Slovene students that studied in [[Graz]] and [[Vienna]]. Together with [[Matija Majar]] and [[Lovro Toman]], he was among the authors who elaborated the political demand for a [[United Slovenia]]. After the failure of the revolutionary requests, he again turned to an exclusively academic activity.
==Selected bibliography== * ''Lexicon linguae slovenicae veteris dialecti'', 1850 (1862-65 als ''Lexicon Palaeoslovenico-graeco-latinum'') * ''Vergleichende Grammatik der slavischen Sprachen'', 4 Bde., 1852–75 * ''Vergleichende Formenlehre der slavischen Sprachen'', 582 pages, 1856, mainly consisting of the 3rd book of ''Vergleichende Grammatik'', and for which he was awarded the [[Volney prize]] * [https://archive.org/details/monumentaserbic00miklgoog Monumenta Serbica Spectantia Historiam Serbiae, Bosniae, Ragusii], 1858 (Hg.) * ''Die Bildung der slavischen Personennamen'', 1860 * [https://archive.org/details/etymologischesw00mikluoft Etymologisches Wörterbuch der slavischen Sprachen], 1886 * [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_pMNi8TcDlEEC Über die Mundarten und Wanderungen der Zigeuner Europas], 12 Tle., 1872-80.
