{{Infobox person | name = Kristoffer von Hassel | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = {{birth year and age|2009}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | parents = Robert Davies and Jill Nyahay | nationality = American | other_names = | occupation = Student | known_for = Being the world's youngest hacker }}
'''Kristoffer von Hassel''' is the world's youngest known [[hacker]]<ref name="welivesecurity">{{cite news|last1=Thomas|first1=Karl|title=5 child geniuses destined for a career in cybersecurity|url=http://www.welivesecurity.com/2015/08/11/6-child-geniuses-destined-career-cybersecurity/|accessdate=28 October 2016|work=WeLiveSecurity|publisher=ESET|date=11 August 2015|ref=welivesecurity}}</ref> and notable for being the youngest "security researcher" listed on [[Microsoft]]'s Security Techcenter as having exposed a security vulnerability.<ref name=del1 /> At the age of 5, Hassel exposed security lapses in the [[Microsoft Live]] [[Xbox]] system, prompting wide media coverage, with some journalists highlighting the dropping age of hackers and their technology mastery.
==Personal life== Hassel is the son of Robert Davies, who works in computer security, and Jill Nyahay. They live in [[Ocean Beach, California|Ocean Beach]], California.<ref name=Molina1>{{cite news|last=Molina|first=Brett|title=5-year-old discovers Xbox security flaw, Microsoft rewards him|url=http://www.smh.com.au/digital-life/games/5yearold-discovers-xbox-security-flaw-microsoft-rewards-him-20140405-zqr3j.html |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=5 April 2014 |deadurl=no |accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref> When the media started covering Hassel in early April 2014, he was enrolled in [[Kindergarten]].<ref name=Callaham1>{{cite news|last=Callaham|first=John|title=5-year-old boy finds Xbox One security flaw, Microsoft rewards him with free games|url=http://www.neowin.net/news/five-year-old-boy-finds-xbox-one-security-flaw-microsoft-rewards-him-with-free-games|accessdate=8 April 2014|date=4 April 2014}}</ref>
==Hacking initiative== After wanting to play his father's [[video games]] but having [[parental controls|parental blocks]] preventing it, five-year-old Hassel tried hacking into the Xbox Live system by trying different combinations of passwords. Eventually, he found a [[Backdoor (computing)|back door]] security glitch that allowed him first to enter the wrong password, then in the following screen to enter a series of spaces to unlock the system.<ref name=del1 /> After he had "exploited the security hole", Hassel's parents found him playing the restricted video games and asked him how he gained access. After he showed them, Davies contacted Microsoft to let them know about the security problem.<ref name=Ecarma1>{{cite news|last=Ecarma|first=Jordan|title=5-YEAR-OLD HACKS XBOX LIVE TO ACCESS LOCKED GAME|url=http://www.autoworldnews.com/articles/6887/20140404/5-year-old-hacks-xbox-live-to-access-locked-game.htm |newspaper=Auto World News|date=4 April 2014 |deadurl=no |accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref> Microsoft responded “We’re always listening to our customers and thank them for bringing issues to our attention. We take security seriously at Xbox and fixed the issue as soon as we learned about it.” They also provided Hassel with a free year-long subscription to Microsoft Live Gold, four video games and $50[[USD]].<ref name=Mosely1>{{cite news|last=Mosely|first=Jared|title=Kindergarten hacker: 5 year old breaks into dad’s Xbox Live account|url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/04/04/kindergarten-hacker-5-year-old-breaks-into-dads-xbox-live-account/|accessdate=8 April 2014|newspaper=Venture Beat|date=4 April 2014}}</ref>
On its website, Microsoft has listed Hassel as one of its Security Researchers, of whom he is the youngest.<ref name=del1>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Michel del|title=5-year-old hacker lends Microsoft a hand|url=http://upstart.bizjournals.com/news/technology/2014/04/04/kristoffer-von-hassel-hacks-xbox.html |newspaper=Upstart Biz Journals|date=4 April 2014 |deadurl=no |accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref> Of the people listed on the page as security researchers, he has been called "the most unusual but perhaps the most significant".<ref name=Syeda1>{{cite news|last=Syeda|first=S|title=Microsoft Xbox Security Flaw Exposed by Five Year Old|url=http://www.thenewsreports.com/microsoft-xbox-security-flaw-exposed-by-five-year-old/4543/syedas |newspaper=The News Reports|date=7 April 2014 |deadurl=no |accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Merva|first1=Nick|title=5-year-old Ocean boy exposes Microsoft Xbox Vulnerability |date=April 7, 2014 |url=http://www.10news.com/news/5-year-old-ocean-beach-exposes-microsoft-xbox-vulnerability |deadurl=no |accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref>
Davies has stated that Hassel had also learned "three or four other hacks" by the age of five, including how to bypass [[smartphone]] screen locks.<ref name=Gross1>{{cite news|last=Gross|first=Doug|title=5-year-old boy hacks dad's Xbox account|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/04/tech/gaming-gadgets/5-year-old-xbox-hack/|accessdate=8 April 2014|newspaper=CNN|date=4 April 2014}}</ref>
==Title== Hassel has been identified as the world's youngest hacker, beating out others who have also been quite young. ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' has reported on "teenage tech geniuses"<ref name=huff4>{{cite news|title=Teen Hackers: 10 Stories of Young Code-Crackers|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/18/teen-hackers-10-stories-o_n_1683387.html|accessdate=8 April 2014|newspaper=Huffington Post|date=18 July 2012}}</ref> and ''[[The New York Times]]'' has stated "in some hacking circles, 15 would be considered middle aged." They continue to say that the age for hacking, coding, and tech adaptability continues to drop.<ref name=Glenny1>{{cite news|last=Glenny|first=Misha|title=Tap Into the Gifted Young Hackers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/09/opinion/tap-into-the-gifted-young-hackers.html?_r=0|accessdate=8 April 2014|newspaper=New York Times|date=8 March 2012}}</ref>
