'''Origen of Alexandria'''{{efn|{{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɒr|ɪ|dʒ|ən}}; {{lang-grc-gre|Ὠριγένης}}, ''Ōrigénēs''; [[Coptic language|Coptic]]: Ϩⲱⲣⲓⲕⲉⲛ<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trismegistos.org/nam/detail.php?record=4745|title=Trismegistos People|website=www.trismegistos.org|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref> Origen's Greek name ''Ōrigénēs'' ({{lang|grc|Ὠριγένης}}) probably means "child of [[Horus]]" (from {{lang|grc|Ὧρος}}, "Horus", and {{lang|grc|γένος}}, "born").<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fathers and Heretics |last=Prestige |first=G. L. |year=1940 |chapter=Origen: or, The Claims of Religious Intelligence |series=Bampton Lectures |publisher=SPCK |location=London |page=43 |chapterurl=http://www.earlychurch.org.uk/pdf/origen_prestige.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=4 September 2009}}</ref>}} ({{circa}} 184 – {{circa}} 253),<ref>''The New Catholic Encyclopedia'' (Detroit: Gale, 2003). {{ISBN|978-0-7876-4004-0}}</ref> also known as '''Origen Adamantius''',{{efn|{{lang|grc|Ὠριγένης Ἀδαμάντιος}}, ''Ōrigénēs Adamántios''. The nickname or [[cognomen]] ''Adamantios'' ({{lang|grc|Ἀδαμάντιος}}) derives from Greek ''adámas'' ({{lang|grc|ἀδάμας}}), which means "[[adamant]]", "unalterable", "unbreakable", "unconquerable", "diamond".<ref>{{LSJ|ada/mas|ἀδάμας|ref}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=adamant|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=adamant&searchmode=none|publisher=[[Online Etymology Dictionary]] |accessdate=2014-08-20}}</ref>
}} was an [[Early Christianity|early Christian]] scholar, [[ascetic]],<ref name=richardfinn100>{{cite book|author= Richard Finn | year= 2009| title= Origen and his ascetic legacy, in: Asceticism in the Graeco-Roman World|pages= 100–130|publisher= Cambridge University Press| url= https://dx.doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511609879.005| doi= 10.1017/CBO9780511609879.005| chapter= Origen and his ascetic legacy| isbn= 9780511609879}}</ref> and [[Christian theology|theologian]] who was born and spent the first half of his career in [[Early centers of Christianity#Alexandria|Alexandria]]. He was a prolific writer who wrote roughly 2,000 treatises in multiple branches of [[theology]], including [[textual criticism]], [[exegesis|biblical exegesis]] and [[biblical hermeneutics]], [[homiletics]], and spirituality. He was one of the most influential figures in early Christian theology, [[Christian apologetics|apologetics]], and [[Christian asceticism|asceticism]].<ref name=richardfinn100/>{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26, 64}} He has been described as "the greatest genius the early church ever produced".{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=25}}

Origen sought [[martyr]]dom with his father at a young age, but was prevented from turning himself in to the authorities by his mother. When he was eighteen years old, Origen became a [[Catechesis|catechist]] at the [[Catechetical School of Alexandria]]. He devoted himself to his studies and adopted an ascetic lifestyle as both a [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] and [[Teetotalism|teetotaler]]. He came into conflict with [[Pope Demetrius I of Alexandria|Demetrius]], the bishop of Alexandria, in 231 after he was [[Ordination|ordained]] as a [[presbyter]] by his friend, the bishop of Caesarea, while on a journey to Athens through Palestine. Demetrius condemned Origen for [[insubordination]] and accused him of having [[castration|castrated]] himself and of having taught that even [[Satan]] would eventually attain salvation, an accusation which Origen himself vehemently denied.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=105}} Origen founded the Christian School of Caesarea, where he taught [[logic]], [[cosmology]], [[natural history]], and theology, and became regarded by the churches of [[Syria Palaestina|Palestine]] and [[Arabia Petraea|Arabia]] as the ultimate authority on all matters of theology. He was [[Confessor of the Faith|tortured for his faith]] during the [[Decian persecution]] in 250 and died three to four years later from his injuries.

Origen was able to produce a massive quantity of writings due to the patronage of his close friend [[Ambrose of Alexandria|Ambrose]], who provided him with a team of secretaries to copy his works, making him one of the most prolific writers in all of antiquity. His treatise ''[[On the First Principles]]'' systematically laid out the principles of [[Christian theology]] and became the foundation for later theological writings.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}} He also authored ''[[Contra Celsum]]'', the most influential work of early [[Christian apologetics]],{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}} in which he defended Christianity against the pagan philosopher [[Celsus]], one of [[Criticism of Christianity|its foremost early critics]]. Origen produced the ''[[Hexapla]]'', the first critical edition of the Hebrew Bible, which contained the original Hebrew text as well as five different Greek translations of it, all written in columns, side-by-side. He wrote hundreds of homilies covering almost the entire Bible, [[Allegorical interpretation of the Bible|interpreting many passages as allegorical]]. Origen taught that, before the [[Pre-existence|creation of the material universe]], God had created the souls of all the intelligent beings. These souls, at first fully devoted to God, fell away from him and were given physical bodies. Origen was the first to propose the [[ransom theory of atonement]] in its fully developed form and, though he was probably a [[Subordinationism|Subordinationist]], he also significantly contributed to the development of the concept of the [[Trinity]]. Origen hoped that [[Universalism|all people might eventually attain salvation]], but was always careful to maintain that this was only speculation. He defended [[free will]] and advocated [[Christian pacifism]].

Origen is a [[Church Fathers|Church Father]]{{sfn|Grafton|2011|page=222}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Runia|first1=David T.|title=Philo and the Church Fathers: A Collection of Papers|date=1995|publisher=E. J. Brill|location=Leiden, Germany|isbn=90-04-10355-4|page=118|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3JyM1kul504C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Origen+of+Alexandria+Church+Father#v=onepage&q=Origen&f=false}}</ref>{{sfn|Pope Benedict XVI|2007|pages=24–27}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Litfin|first1=Bryan M.|title=Getting to Know the Church Fathers: An Evangelical Introduction|date=2016|orig-year=2007|publisher=Baker Academic|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|isbn=978-1-4934-0478-0|page=unpaginated|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9RdGDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT124&dq=Origen+of+Alexandria+Church+Father#v=onepage&q=Origen%20of%20Alexandria%20Church%20Father&f=false}}</ref> and is widely regarded as one of the most important Christian theologians of all time.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=99}} His teachings were especially influential in the east, with [[Athanasius of Alexandria]] and the three [[Cappadocian Fathers]] being among his most devoted followers.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}} Argument over the orthodoxy of Origen's teachings spawned the [[First Origenist Crisis]] in the late fourth century AD, in which he was attacked by [[Epiphanius of Salamis]] and [[Jerome]], but defended by [[Tyrannius Rufinus]] and [[John II, Bishop of Jerusalem|John of Jerusalem]]. In 543, the emperor [[Justinian I]] condemned him as a heretic and ordered all his writings to be burned. The [[Second Council of Constantinople]] in 553 may have [[Anathema|anathemized]] Origen, or it may have only condemned certain heretical teachings which claimed to be derived from Origen. His teachings on the [[pre-existence]] of [[Soul#Christianity|souls]] were rejected by the Church.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The salvation of Satan|first=C.&nbsp;A.|last=Patrides|authorlink=Constantinos Patrides|journal=Journal of the History of Ideas|volume=28|date=October–December 1967|pages=467–478|jstor=2708524|ref=harv|issue=4 |doi=10.2307/2708524}} reprinted in {{cite book |chapter='A principle of infinite love': The salvation of Satan|title=Premises and motifs in Renaissance literature|first=C. A.|last=Patrides|origyear=1967|year=1982|pages=|jstor=2708524|ref=harv|publisher=Princeton University Press|location=Princeton, New Jersey |<!-- authorlink=Constantinos A. Patrides -->}}</ref>

==Life==

===Early years===
Almost all information about Origen's life comes from a lengthy biography of him in Book VI of the ''[[Church History (Eusebius)|Ecclesiastical History]]'' written by the later Christian historian [[Eusebius]] ({{circa}} 260 – {{circa}} 340).{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=9}} Eusebius portrays Origen as the perfect Christian scholar and as a literal saint.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=9}} Eusebius, however, wrote this account almost fifty years after Origen's death and had access to few reliable sources on Origen's life, especially his early years.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=9}} Anxious for more material about his hero, Eusebius recorded events based on only unreliable hearsay evidence and frequently made speculative inferences about Origen based on the sources he had available.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=9}} Nonetheless, scholars can reconstruct a general impression of Origen's historical life by sorting out the parts of Eusebius's account that are accurate from those that are inaccurate.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=9–10}}

Origen was born in either 185 or 186 AD in [[Alexandria]].{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=2}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=8}} According to Eusebius, Origen's father was [[Leonides of Alexandria]], a respected professor of literature and also a devout Christian who practiced his religion openly.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=10}} Joseph Wilson Trigg deems the details of this report unreliable, but states that Origen's father was certainly "a prosperous and thoroughly Hellenized bourgeois".{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=10}} According to John Anthony McGuckin, Origen's mother, whose name is unknown, may have been a member of the lower class who did not have the [[Roman citizenship|right of citizenship]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}} It is likely that, on account of his mother's status, Origen himself was not a Roman citizen.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=2–3}} Origen's father taught him about literature and philosophy,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=3–4}} and also about the Bible and Christian doctrine.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=3–4}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=11–16}} Eusebius states that Origen's father made him memorize passages of scripture daily.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=12}} Trigg accepts this tradition as possibly genuine, given Origen's ability as an adult to recite extended passages of scripture at will.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=12}} Eusebius also reports that Origen became so learned about the holy scriptures at an early age that his father was unable to answer his questions.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=12–13}}

In 202, when Origen was "not yet seventeen", the [[Roman emperor]] [[Septimius Severus]] ordered Roman citizens [[Persecution of Christians in the Roman Empire#Marcus Aurelius to Maximinus the Thracian|who openly practiced Christianity to be executed]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=30}} Origen's father Leonides was arrested and thrown in prison.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=30}} Eusebius reports that Origen wanted to turn himself in to the authorities so they would execute him as well,{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}} but his mother hid all his clothes and he was unable to go to the authorities since he refused to leave the house naked.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}} According to McGuckin, even if Origen had turned himself in, it is unlikely that he would have been punished, since the emperor was only intent on executing Roman citizens.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}} Origen's father was beheaded{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=30}} and the state confiscated the family's entire property, leaving them broken and impoverished.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=30}} Origen was the eldest of nine children{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=30}} and, as his father's heir, it became his responsibility to provide for the whole family.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=3}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=30}}

[[File:OrigenStudentsLuyken.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Dutch illustration by Jan Luyken (1700), showing Origen teaching his students]]

When he was eighteen years old, Origen was appointed as a [[Catechesis|catechist]] at the [[Catechetical School of Alexandria]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}} Many scholars have assumed that Origen became the head of the school,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}} but, according to McGuckin, this is highly improbable and it is more likely that he was simply given a paid teaching position, perhaps as a "relief effort" for his destitute family.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}} While employed at the school, he adopted the [[asceticism|ascetic]] lifestyle of the Greek [[Sophist]]s.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}}<ref name="EusebiusHistoria" /> He spent the whole day teaching{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}} and would stay up late at night writing treatises and commentaries.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}} He went barefoot and only owned one cloak.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}} He was a [[teetotalism|teetotaler]]{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=102}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} and a [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]]{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=102}} and he often fasted for long periods of time.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}} Although Eusebius goes to great lengths to portray Origen as one of the [[Christian monasticism|Christian monastics]] of his own era,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}} this portrayal is now generally recognized as [[Anachronism|anachronistic]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=4}}

According to Eusebius, as a young man, Origen was taken in by a wealthy [[Gnosticism|Gnostic]] woman,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} who was also the patron of a very influential Gnostic theologian from [[Antioch]], who frequently lectured in her home.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} Eusebius goes to great lengths to insist that, although Origen studied while in her home,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} he never once "prayed in common" with her or the Gnostic theologian.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} Later, Origen succeeded in converting a wealthy man named Ambrose from [[Valentinianism|Valentinian Gnosticism]] to orthodox Christianity.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} Ambrose was so impressed by the young scholar that he gave Origen a house, a secretary, seven [[Shorthand|stenographers]], a crew of copyists and calligraphers, and paid for all of his writings to be published.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}}

Sometime when he was in his early twenties, Origen sold the small library of Greek literary works which he had inherited from his father for a sum which netted him a daily income of four [[Obolus|obols]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}}<ref name="EusebiusHistoria">Eusebius, ''Historia Ecclesiastica'', VI.3.9</ref> He used this money to continue his study of the Bible and philosophy.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}} Origen studied at numerous schools throughout Alexandria,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} including the [[Alexandrian school|Platonic Academy of Alexandria]],{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=100–101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}} where he was a student of [[Ammonius Saccas]].{{sfn|Watts|2008|pages=158–161}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=5}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=66–75}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} Eusebius claims that Origen studied under [[Clement of Alexandria]],{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=54–66}} but, according to McGuckin, this is almost certainly a retrospective assumption based on the similarity of their teachings.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} Origen himself rarely mentions Clement in his own writings{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} and, when he does, it is usually to correct him.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}}

===Alleged self-castration===
{{multiple image
| align     = right
| direction = horizontal
| footer   = Eusebius claims in his ''Ecclesiastical History'' that, as a young man, Origen secretly paid a physician to surgically [[castration|castrate]] him, a claim which affected Origen's reputation for centuries,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=6, 13–14}} as demonstrated by these fifteenth-century depictions of Origen castrating himself.
| width     = 
<!-- Image 1 -->
| image1    = Origen emasculating himself (MS. Douce 195).jpg
| width1    = 300
<!-- Image 2 -->
| image2    = A-depiction-of-Origens-self-castration.jpg
| width2    = 150
}}

Eusebius claims that, as a young man, following a literal misreading of {{bibleverse|Matthew|19:12}}, in which Jesus is presented as saying "there are eunuchs who have made themselves eunuch for the sake of the [[Kingdom of Heaven (Gospel of Matthew)|kingdom of heaven]]", Origen went to a physician and paid him to surgically [[castration|remove his genitals]] in order to ensure his reputation as a respectable tutor to young men and women.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}}<ref>Eusebius, ''Historia Ecclesiastica'' VI.8</ref><ref>http://image.ox.ac.uk/images/bodleian/msdouce195/122v.jpg</ref> Eusebius further alleges that Origen privately told [[Pope Demetrius I of Alexandria|Demetrius]], the bishop of Alexandria, about the castration and that Demetrius initially praised him for his devotion to God on account of it.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} Origen himself, however, never mentions anything about having castrated himself in any of his surviving writings{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=54}} and, in his exegesis of this verse in his ''Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew'', written near the end of life, he strongly condemns any literal interpretation of Matthew 19:12,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} asserting that only an idiot would interpret the passage as advocating literal castration.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}}

Since the beginning of the twentieth century, some scholars have questioned the historicity of Origen's self-castration, with many seeing it as a wholesale fabrication.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Shawn W. J. |last=Keough |year=2008 |volume=03 |issue=30 |title=Christoph Markschies, ''Origenes und sein Erbe: Gesammelte Studien. Texte und Untersuchungen zur Geschichte der altchristlichen Literatur 160'' |journal=Bryn Mawr Classical Review |url=http://ccat.sas.upenn.edu/bmcr/2008/2008-03-30.html |accessdate=2009-01-25}}</ref><ref name="Origen and Origenism">{{cite CE1913 |last=Prat |first=Ferdinand |wstitle=Origen and Origenism |volume=11}}</ref> Trigg states that Eusebius's account of Origen's self-castration is certainly true, because Eusebius, who was an ardent admirer of Origen, yet clearly describes the castration as an act of pure folly, would have had no motive to pass on a piece of information that might tarnish Origen's reputation unless it was "notorious and beyond question."{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}} Trigg sees Origen's condemnation of the literal interpretation of Matthew 19:12 as him "tacitly repudiating the literalistic reading he had acted on in his youth."{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=53}}

In sharp contrast, McGuckin dismisses Eusebius's story of Origen's self-castration as "hardly credible", seeing it as a deliberate attempt by Eusebius to distract from more serious questions regarding the orthodoxy of Origen's teachings.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} McGuckin also states, "We have no indication that the motive of castration for respectability was ever regarded as standard by a teacher of mixed-gender classes."{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} He adds that Origen's female students (whom Eusebius lists by name) would have been accompanied by attendants at all times, meaning Origen would have had no good reason to think that anyone would suspect him of impropriety.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=6}} [[Henry Chadwick (theologian)|Henry Chadwick]] argues that, while Eusebius's story may be true, it seems unlikely, given that Origen's exposition of Matthew 19:12 "strongly deplored any literal interpretation of the words".{{sfn|Chadwick|1993|pages=108–109}} Instead, Chadwick suggests, "Perhaps Eusebius was uncritically reporting malicious gossip retailed by Origen's enemies, of whom there were many."{{sfn|Chadwick|1993|pages=108–109}} However, many noted historians, such as [[Peter Brown (historian)|Peter Brown]] and [[William Placher]], continue to find no reason to conclude that the story is false.<ref name="Platcher">[[William Placher]], ''A History of Christian Theology: An Introduction,'' (Philadelphia: Westminster Press, 1983), p62.</ref> Placher theorizes that, if it is true, it may have followed an episode in which Origen received some raised eyebrows while privately tutoring a woman.<ref name="Platcher"/>

===Travels and early writings===
{{
