In his early twenties, Origen became less interested in being a grammarian{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=7}} and more interested in being a rhetor-philosopher.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=7}} He gave his job as a catechist to his younger colleague [[Pope Heraclas of Alexandria|Heraclas]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=7}} Meanwhile, Origen began to style himself as a "master of philosophy".{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=7}} Origen's new position as a self-styled Christian philosopher brought him into conflict with Demetrius, the bishop of Alexandria.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=7}} Demetrius was a charismatic leader who ruled the Christian congregation of Alexandria with an iron fist{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=7}} and he was the one who was most directly responsible for the elevation of the bishop of Alexandria;{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=7–8}} prior to Demetrius, the bishop of Alexandria had merely been a priest who was elected to represent his fellows,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} but after Demetrius, the bishop was seen as clearly a rank higher than his fellow priests.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} By styling himself as an independent philosopher, Origen was reviving a role that had been prominent in earlier Christianity,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=7–8}} but which challenged the authority of the now-powerful bishop.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=7–8}}

Meanwhile, Origen began composing his massive theological treatise ''[[On the First Principles]]'',{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} a landmark book which systematically laid out the foundations of Christian theology for centuries to come.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} Origen also began travelling abroad to visit schools across the Mediterranean.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} In 212 AD, he travelled to Rome, which was a major center of philosophy at the time.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} In Rome, Origen attended lectures by [[Hippolytus of Rome]] and was influenced by his ''[[Logos (Christianity)|logos]]'' theology.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} In 213 or 214, the governor of Arabia sent a message to the prefect of Egypt requesting him to send Origen to meet with him so that he could interview him and learn more about Christianity from its leading intellectual.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} Origen was escorted by official bodyguards{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=8}} and spent a short time in Arabia with the governor before returning to Alexandria.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=8–9}}

In the autumn of 215, the Roman emperor [[Caracalla]] visited Alexandria.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} During the visit, the students at the schools there protested and made fun of him for having murdered his brother [[Geta (emperor)|Geta]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} Caracalla was incensed and ordered his troops to ravage the city, execute the governor, and kill all the protesters.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} He also commanded them to expel all the teachers and intellectuals from the city.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} Origen fled Alexandria and travelled to the city of [[Caesarea Maritima]] in Roman province of [[Syria Palaestina|Palestine]],{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} where the bishops [[Theoctistus of Caesarea]] and [[Alexander of Jerusalem]] became his devoted admirers{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} and asked him to deliver discourses on the scriptures in their respective churches.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} This effectively amounted to letting Origen deliver homilies, even though he was not formally ordained.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} While this was not at all a completely unexpected phenomenon, especially given Origen's international fame as a teacher and philosopher,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} it infuriated Demetrius, who saw it as a direct undermining of his authority.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} Demetrius sent deacons from Alexandria to demand that the Palestinian hierarchs immediately return "his" catechist to Alexandria.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=9}} He also issued a decree chastising the Palestinians for allowing a person who was not ordained to preach.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=9–10}} The Palestinian bishops, in turn, issued their own condemnation, accusing Demetrius of being jealous of Origen's fame and prestige.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}}

[[File:1 QIsa example of damage col 12-13.jpg|thumb|While in [[Jericho]], Origen bought an ancient manuscript of the Hebrew Bible which had been discovered "in a jar",{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} a discovery which prefigures the later discovery of the [[Dead Sea Scrolls]] in the twentieth century.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} Shown here is a section of the [[Isaiah scroll]] from [[Qumran]].]]

Origen obeyed Demetrius's order and returned to Alexandria,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} bringing with him an antique scroll he had purchased at [[Jericho]] containing the full text of the Hebrew Bible.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} The manuscript, which had purportedly been found "in a jar",{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} became the source text for one of the two Hebrew columns in Origen's ''[[Hexapla]]'', the first critical edition of the Old Testament, containing two versions of the Hebrew text and four Greek translations of it, all written in columns next to each other.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} Origen studied the Old Testament in great depth;{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} Eusebius even claims that Origen learned Hebrew.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=11}}{{sfn|Marcos|2000|page=205}} Most modern scholars agree that this is implausible,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=11}}{{sfn|Marcos|2000|pages=204–205}} but they disagree on how much Origen actually knew about the language.{{sfn|Marcos|2000|page=205}} H. Lietzmann concludes that Origen probably only knew the Hebrew alphabet and not much else;{{sfn|Marcos|2000|page=205}} whereas, R. P. C. Hanson and G. Bardy argue that Origen had a superficial understanding of the language, but not enough to have composed the entire ''Hexapla''.{{sfn|Marcos|2000|page=205}} A note in Origen's ''On the First Principles'' mentions an unknown "Hebrew master",{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=11}} but this was probably a consultant, not a teacher.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=11}}

Origen also studied the entire New Testament,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} but especially the [[Pauline epistles|epistles of the apostle Paul]] and the [[Gospel of John]],{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} the writings which Origen regarded as the most important and authoritative.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=10}} At Ambrose's request, Origen composed the first five books of his exhaustive ''Commentary on the Gospel of John'',{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=12}} He also wrote the first eight books of his ''Commentary on Genesis'', his ''Commentary on Psalms 1-25'', and his ''Commentary on Lamentations''.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=12}} In addition to these commentaries, Origen also wrote two books on the resurrection of Jesus and ten books of ''Stromata''.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=12}} It is likely that these works contained much theological speculation,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=13}} which brought Origen into even greater conflict with Demetrius.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=13}}

===Conflict with Demetrius and removal to Caesarea===

Origen repeatedly asked Demetrius to [[Ordination|ordain]] him as a priest, but Demetrius continually refused.<ref>[[Eusebius]], ''Church History'', VI.14. See [http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/250106.htm Eusebius - Church History (Book VI)].</ref>{{sfn|Griggs|2000|page=61}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}} In around 231, Demetrius sent Origen on a mission to Athens.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=13}}{{sfn|Crouzel|1989|page=18}} Along the way, Origen stopped in Caesarea,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=13}}{{sfn|Crouzel|1989|page=18}} where he was warmly greeted by the bishops Theoctistus and Alexander of Jerusalem, who had become his close friends during his previous stay.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=13}}{{sfn|Crouzel|1989|page=18}} While he was visiting Caesarea, Origen asked Theoctistus to ordain him as a priest.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=13}} Theoctistus gladly complied.<ref>Eusebius, ''Historia Ecclesiastica'' VI.26</ref>{{sfn|Griggs|2000|page=61}}{{sfn|Crouzel|1989|page=18}} Upon learning of Origen's ordination, Demetrius was outraged and issued a condemnation declaring that Origen's ordination by a foreign bishop was an act of [[insubordination]].{{sfn|Griggs|2000|page=61}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=13–14}}{{sfn|Crouzel|1989|page=18}}

Eusebius reports that, as a result of Demetrius's condemnations, Origen decided not to return to Alexandria and to instead take up permanent residence in Caesarea.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=13–14}} John Anthony McGuckin, however, argues that Origen had probably already been planning to stay in Caesarea.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=14}} The Palestinian bishops declared Origen the chief theologian of Caesarea.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}} [[Firmilian]], the bishop of [[Caesarea Mazaca]] in [[Cappadocia]], was such a devoted disciple of Origen that he begged him to come to Cappadocia and teach there.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=14–15}}

Demetrius raised a storm of protests against the bishops of Palestine and the church [[synod]] in Rome itself.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=14}} According to Eusebius, Demetrius published the allegation that Origen had secretly castrated himself,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=14}} a capital offense under Roman law at the time{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=14}} and one which would have made Origen's ordination invalid, since eunuchs were forbidden from becoming priests.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=14}} Demetrius also alleged that Origen had taught an extreme form of ''[[apokatastasis]]'', which held that all beings, including even [[Satan]] himself, would eventually attain salvation.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}} This allegation probably arose from a misunderstanding of Origen's argument during a debate with the Valentinian Gnostic teacher Candidus.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}} Candidus had argued in favor of [[predestination]] by declaring that the Devil was beyond salvation.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}} Origen had responded by arguing that, if the Devil is destined for eternal damnation, it was on account of his actions, which were the result of his own [[free will]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=15–16}} Therefore, Origen had declared that Satan was only morally [[Reprobation|reprobate]], not absolutely reprobate.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=15–16}}

Demetrius died in 232, within less than a year after Origen's departure from Alexandria.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=14}} The accusations against Origen faded with the death of Demetrius,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}} but they did not disappear entirely{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=15–17}} and they continued to haunt him for the rest of his career.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=15–17}} Origen defended himself in his ''Letter to Friends in Alexandria'',{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}} in which he vehemently denied that he had ever taught that the Devil would attain salvation{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=105}}{{sfn|Kelly|2006|page=199}} and insisted that the very notion of the Devil attaining salvation was simply ludicrous.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}}

===Work and teaching in Caesarea===
{{rquote|right|It was like a spark falling in our deepest soul, setting it on fire, making it burst into flame within us. It was, at the same time, a love for the Holy Word, the most beautiful object of all that, by its ineffable beauty attracts all things to itself with irresistible force, and it was also love for this man, the friend and advocate of the Holy Word. I was thus persuaded to give up all other goals... I had only one remaining object that I valued and longed for - philosophy, and that divine man who was my master of philosophy.|Theodore, ''Panegyric'', a first-hand account of what listening to one of Origen's lectures in Caesarea was like{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}}}}

During his early years in Caesarea, Origen's primary task was the establishment of a Christian School;{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=16}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|pages=161–164}} Caesarea had long been seen as a center of learning for Jews and Hellenistic philosophers,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=16}} but, until Origen's arrival, it had lacked a Christian center of higher education.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=16}} According to Eusebius, the school Origen founded was primarily targeted towards young pagans who had expressed interest in Christianity,{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|pages=161–164}} but were not yet ready to ask for baptism.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|pages=161–164}} The school therefore sought to explain Christian teachings through Middle Platonism.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|pages=161–166}} Origen started his curriculum by teaching his students classical Socratic reasoning.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}} After they had mastered this, he taught them [[cosmology]] and [[natural history]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}} Finally, once they had mastered all of these subjects, he taught them theology, which was the highest of all philosophies, the accumulation of everything they had learning previously.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}}

With the establishment of the Caesarean school, Origen's reputation as a scholar and theologian reached its zenith{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=16}} and he became known throughout the Mediterranean world as a brilliant intellectual.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=16}} The [[ordinary (officer)|hierarchs]] of the Palestinian and Arabian church synods regarded Origen as the ultimate expert on all matters dealing with theology.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}} While teaching in Caesarea, Origen resumed work on his ''Commentary on John'', composing at least books six through ten.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=16–17}} In the first of these books, Origen compares himself to "an Israelite who has escaped the perverse persecution of the Egyptians."{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=16}} Origen also wrote the treatise ''On Prayer'' at the request of his friend Ambrose and his "sister" Tatiana,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}} in which he analyzes the different types of prayers described in the Bible and offers a detailed exegesis on the [[Lord's Prayer]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}}

[[File:Julia mammea02 pushkin.jpg|thumb|left|[[Julia Avita Mamaea]], the mother of the Roman emperor [[Severus Alexander]], summoned Origen to Antioch to teach her philosophy.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}]]

Not only Christians, but also pagans took a fascination with Origen.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}} The Neoplatonist philosopher [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] heard of Origen's fame{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}} and travelled to Caesarea to listen to his lectures.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}} Porphyry recounts that Origen had extensively studied the teachings of [[Pythagoras]], [[Plato]], and [[Aristotle]],{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=552}} but also those of important Middle Platonists, [[Neopythagoreanism|Neopythagoreans]], and [[Stoicism|Stoics]], including [[Numenius of Apamea]], [[Chronius]], [[Apollophanes]], [[On the Sublime|Longinus]], [[Moderatus of Gades]], [[Nicomachus]], [[Chaeremon]], and [[Lucius Annaeus Cornutus|Cornutus]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=552}} Nonetheless, Porphyry accused Origen of having betrayed true philosophy by subjugating its insights to the exegesis of the Christian scriptures.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=18}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|page=158}} Eusebius reports that Origen was summoned from Caesarea to Antioch at the behest of [[Julia Avita Mamaea]], the mother of the Roman emperor [[Severus Alexander]], "to discuss Christian philosophy and doctrine with her."<ref>From ''The Emergence of Christianity'', Cynthia White, Greenwood Press, 2007, p. 14.</ref>

In 235, approximately three years after Origen began teaching in Caesarea, Alexander Severus, who had been tolerant towards Christians, was murdered{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} and the new emperor [[Maximinus Thrax]] instigated a purge of all those who had supported his predecessor.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} His [[pogrom]]s targeted Christian leaders{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} and, in Rome, [[Pope Pontianus]] and [[Hippolytus of Rome]] were both sent into exile.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} Origen knew that he was in danger and went into hiding in the home of a faithful Christian woman named Juliana the Virgin,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} who had been a student of the [[Ebionites|Ebionite]] leader [[Symmachus (translator)|Symmachus]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} Origen's close friend and longtime patron Ambrose was arrested in [[Nicomedia]] and Protoctetes, the leading priest in Caesarea, was also arrested.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} In their honor, Origen composed his treatise ''[[Exhortation to Martyrdom]]'',{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}}{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=122}} which is now regarded as one of the greatest classics of Christian resistance literature.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} After coming out of hiding following Maximinus's death, Origen founded a school where Gregory Thaumaturgus, later bishop of Pontus, was one of the pupils. He preached regularly on Wednesdays and Fridays, and later daily.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|page=165}}

===Later life===

Sometime between 238 and 244, Origen visited Athens, where he completed his ''Commentary on the [[Book of Ezekiel]]'' and began writing his ''Commentary on the [[Song of Songs]]''.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=20}} After visiting Athens, he visited Ambrose in Nicomedia.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=20}} According to Porphyry, Origen also travelled to Rome or Antioch, where he met [[Plotinus]], the founder of Neoplatonism.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=20–21}} The Christians of the eastern Mediterranean continued to revere Origen as the most orthodox of all theologians{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=21}} and, when the Palestinian hierarchs learned that [[Beryllus of Bostra|Beryllus]], the bishop of Bostra and one of the most energetic Christian leaders of the time, had been preaching [[adoptionism]] (i.e., belief that Jesus was born human and only became divine after his baptism),{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=21}} they sent Origen to convert him to orthodoxy.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=21}} Origen engaged Beryllus in a public disputation, which went so successfully that Beryllus promised to only teach Origen's theology from then on.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=21}} On another occasion, a Christian leader in Arabia named Heracleides began teaching that the [[Christian mortalism|soul was mortal and that it perished with the body]].{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} Origen refuted these teachings, arguing that the soul is immortal and can never die.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}}

In {{circa}} 249, the [[Plague of Cyprian]] broke out.{{sfn|MacMullen|1992|page=}} In 250, Emperor [[Decius]], believing that the plague was caused by Christians' failure to recognise him as Divine,{{sfn|MacMullen|1992|page=}} [[Decian persecution|issued a decree for Christians to be persecuted]].{{sfn|MacMullen|1992|page=}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} This time Origen did not escape.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} Eusebius recounts how Origen suffered "bodily tortures and torments under the iron collar and in the dungeon; and how for many days with his feet stretched four spaces in the stocks".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://christianbookshelf.org/pamphilius/church_history/chapter_xxxix_the_persecution_under_decius.htm |title=Eusebius, '&#39;Ecclesiastical History'&#39;, Book 6, chapter 39 |publisher=Christianbookshelf.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref><ref>Timothy David Barnes, ''Constantine and Eusebius'', page 351, footnote 96 (Cambridge, Mass.; London: Harvard University Press, 1981) {{ISBN|0-674-16530-6}}</ref>{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} The governor of Caesarea gave very specific orders that Origen was not to be killed until he had publicly renounced in faith in Christ.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} Origen endured two years of imprisonment and torture,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} but obstinately refused to renounce his faith.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=3, 22}} In 252, the emperor Decius was assassinated and Origen was released from prison.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} Nonetheless, Origen's health was broken by the physical tortures enacted on him{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=3, 23}} and he died less than a year later at the age of sixty-nine.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=102}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=3, 23}} A later legend, recounted by [[Jerome]] and numerous itineraries, places his death and burial at [[Tyre (Lebanon)|Tyre]], but little value can be attached to this.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Jerome |title=[[De Viris Illustribus (Jerome)|De viris illustribus (On Illustrious Men)]] |chapter=[[s:De Viris Illustribus#Chapter 54 (Origen, surnamed Adamantius)|Chapter 54 (Origen, surnamed Adamantius)]] |authorlink=Jerome}}</ref>

==Works==
[[File:Origen.jpg|thumb|left|Imaginative portrayal of Origen from "Les Vrais Portraits Et Vies Des Hommes Illustres" by [[André Thévet]]]]

===Exegetical writings===
Origen was an extremely prolific writer.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=245}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|pages=154–155}}{{sfn|Watts|2008|page=159}} According to [[Epiphanius of Salamis|Epiphanius]], he wrote a grand total of roughly 6,000 works over the course of his lifetime.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}}<ref>''Haer''., lxiv.63</ref> Most scholars agree that this estimate is probably somewhat exaggerated.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} According to Jerome, Eusebius listed the titles of just under 2,000 treatises written by Origen in his lost ''Life of Pamphilus''.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}}<ref>''[[Church History (Eusebius)|Ecclesiastical History]]'', VI., xxxii. 3; Eng. transl., ''[[NPNF]]'', 2 ser., i. 277</ref><ref>''Epist. ad Paulam, NPNF'', vi. 46</ref> Jerome compiled an abbreviated list of Origen's major treatises, itemizing 800 different titles.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}}

By far the most important work of Origen on textual criticism was the ''[[Hexapla]]'' ("Sixfold"), a massive comparative study of various translations of the Old Testament in six columns:{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=10, 27}} [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], Hebrew in Greek characters, the [[Septuagint]], and the Greek translations of [[Theodotion]] (a Jewish scholar from {{circa}} 180 AD), [[Aquila of Sinope]] (another Jewish scholar from {{circa}} 117-138), and [[Symmachus (translator)|Symmachus]] (an [[Ebionites|Ebionite]] scholar from {{circa}} 193-211).{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=10, 27}}<ref>Trigg, Joseoph W. - ''Origen - The Early Church Fathers'' - 1998, Routledge, London and New York, page 16. Retrieved 2 September 2015.</ref> Origen was the first Christian scholar to introduce critical markers to a Biblical text.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} He marked the Septuagint column of the ''Hexapla'' using signs adapted from those used by the textual critics of the [[Library of Alexandria|Great Library of Alexandria]]:{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} a passage found in the Septuagint that was not found in the Hebrew text would be marked with an ''[[asterisk]]'' (*){{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} and a passage that was found in other Greek translations, but not in the Septuagint, would be marked with an ''[[obelus]]'' (÷).{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}}

[[File:Texts of the OT.svg|thumb|right|upright=1.3|Diagram showing the inter-relationship between various significant ancient versions and recensions of the Old Testament (some identified by their siglum). LXX here denotes the original septuagint.]]

The ''Hexapla'' was the cornerstone of the Great Library of Caesarea, which Origen founded.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} It was still the centerpiece of the library's collection by the time of Jerome,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} who records having used it in his letters on multiple occasions.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} When the emperor [[Constantine the Great]] ordered fifty complete copies of the Bible to be transcribed and disseminated across the empire, Eusebius used the ''Hexapla'' as the master copy for the Old Testament.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} Although the original ''Hexapla'' has been lost,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=27–28}} the text of it has survived in numerous fragments{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} and a more-or-less complete Syraic copy of it made by the seventh-century bishop Paul of Tella has also survived.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=27–28}} For some sections of the ''Hexapla'', Origen also added additional columns containing other Greek translations;{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} for the Book of Psalms, he included no less than eight Greek translations, making this section known as ''Enneapla'' ("Ninefold").{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}} Origen also produced the ''Tetrapla'' ("Fourfold"), a smaller, abridged version of the ''Hexapla'' containing only the four Greek translations and not the original Hebrew text.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=27}}

According to Jerome's ''Epistle'' 33, Origen wrote extensive ''[[scholia]]'' on the books of [[Book of Exodus|Exodus]], [[Leviticus]], [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]], Psalms 1-15, [[Ecclesiastes]], and the Gospel of John.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} None of these ''scholia'' have survived intact,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} but parts of them were incorporated into the ''[[Catena (biblical commentary)|Catenaea]]'', a collection of excerpts from major works of Biblical commentary written by the Church Fathers.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} Other fragments of the ''scholia'' are preserved in Origen's ''[[Philokalia (Origen)|Philocalia]]'' and in [[Pamphilus of Caesarea]]'s apology for Origen.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} The ''Stromateis'' were of a similar character, and the margin of ''Codex Athous Laura'', 184, contains citations from this work on Rom. 9:23; I Cor. 6:14, 7:31, 34, 9:20-21, 10:9, besides a few other fragments. Origen composed homilies covering almost the entire Bible. There are 205, and possibly 279, homilies of Origen that are extant either in Greek or in Latin translations.{{efn|The discrepancy concerns the 74 homilies on the Psalms attributed to Jerome, but which V Peri has argued Jerome translated from Origen with only minor changes. (Both 205 and 279 exclude the 2012 discoveries) {{harvnb|Heine|2004|page=124}}}}

[[File:Papyrus Bodmer VIII.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.3|Two sides of the ''[[Papyrus 72|Papyrus Bodmer VIII]]'', an early New Testament fragment from the third or fourth century AD containing the [[Epistle of Jude]], [[First Epistle of Peter|1 Peter]], and [[Second Epistle of Peter|2 Peter]]. Origen accepted the two former as authentic without question,{{sfn|Lockett|2017|pages=71–72}} but noted that the latter was suspected to be a forgery.{{sfn|Lockett|2017|page=71}}]]

The homilies preserved are on Genesis (16), Exodus (13), Leviticus (16), Numbers (28), Joshua (26), Judges (9), I Sam. (2), Psalms 36-38 (9),{{efn|And possibly the extra 74 homilies on the Psalms. {{harvnb|Heine|2004|page=124}}}} Canticles (2), Isaiah (9), Jeremiah (7 Greek, 2 Latin, 12 Greek and Latin), Ezekiel (14), and Luke (39). The homilies were preached in the church at Caesarea, with the exception of the two on 1 Samuel which were delivered in Jerusalem. Nautin has argued that they were all preached in a three-year liturgical cycle some time between 238 and 244, preceding the ''Commentary on the Song of Songs'', where Origen refers to homilies on Judges, Exodus, Numbers, and a work on Leviticus.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=125}} On June 11, 2012, the [[Bavarian State Library]] announced that the Italian philologist Marina Molin Pradel had discovered twenty-nine previously unknown homilies by Origen in a twelfth-century Byzantine manuscript from their collection.<ref name=hom2012>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=June 12, 2012 |url=https://news.yahoo.com/vatican-reports-discovery-ancient-documents-175855191.html |title=Vatican reports discovery of ancient documents |accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roger-pearse.com/weblog/2012/06/11/greek-text-found-of-origens-homilies-on-the-psalms/ |title=Greek text found of Origen’s homilies on the Psalms! at Roger Pearse |publisher=Roger-pearse.com |date=2012-06-11 |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref> Prof. Lorenzo Perrone of the Bologna University and other experts confirmed the authenticity of the homilies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alinsuciu.com/2012/06/12/lorenzo-perrone-about-origens-newly-discovered-homilies-on-the-psalms/ |title=Lorenzo Perrone About Origen’s Newly Discovered Homilies on the Psalms |publisher=Alin Suciu |date=2012-06-12 |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref> The texts of these manuscripts can be found online.<ref>[http://bsb-mdz12-spiegel.bsb.lrz.de/~db/0005/bsb00050972/images/ Digitalisat] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120817011126/http://bsb-mdz12-spiegel.bsb.lrz.de/~db/0005/bsb00050972/images/ |date=August 17, 2012 }}</ref>

Origen is the main source of information on the use of the texts that were later officially canonized as the [[New Testament]].{{sfn|Lockett|2017|pages=71–73}}<ref name="Bateman">[http://ssrn.com/abstract=1653073 C.G. Bateman, Origen’s Role in the Formation of the New Testament Canon, 2010]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20121102173142/http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1653073 archive]</ref> The information used to create the late-fourth-century [[Easter Letter]], which declared accepted Christian writings, was probably based on the lists given in Eusebius's ''Ecclesiastical History'' HE 3:25 and 6:25, which were both primarily based on information provided by Origen.<ref name="Bateman"/> Origen accepted the authenticity of the epistles of [[First Epistle of John|1 John]], [[First Epistle of Peter|1 Peter]], and [[Epistle of Jude|Jude]] without question{{sfn|Lockett|2017|pages=71–73}} and accepted the [[Epistle of James]] as authentic with only slight hesitation.{{sfn|Lockett|2017|page=72}} He also refers to [[Second Epistle of John|2 John]], [[Third Epistle of John|3 John]], and [[Second Epistle of Peter|2 Peter]],{{sfn|Lockett|2017|pages=71–72}} but notes that all three were suspected to be forgeries.{{sfn|Lockett|2017|pages=71–72}} Origen may have also considered other writings to be "inspired" that were rejected by later authors, including the [[Epistle of Barnabas]], [[Shepherd of Hermas]], and [[1 Clement]].<ref name="McGuckin2001">McGuckin, John A. "Origen as Literary Critic in the Alexandrian Tradition." 121-37 in vol. 1 of 'Origeniana octava: Origen and the Alexandrian Tradition.' Papers of the 8th International Origen Congress (Pisa, 27–31 August 2001). Edited by L. Perrone. Bibliotheca Ephemeridum theologicarum Lovaniensium 164. 2 vols. Leuven: Leuven University Press, 2003.</ref> "Origen is not the originator of the idea of biblical canon, but he certainly gives the philosophical and literary-interpretative underpinnings for the whole notion."<ref name="McGuckin2001"/>

===Extant commentaries===
[[File:Origenes Opera.JPG|thumb|upright=1.5|A set of manuscripts containing Latin translations of some of Origen's extant writings]]

Origen's commentaries written on specific books of scripture are much more focused on systematic exegesis than his homilies.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}} In these writings, Origen applies the precise critical methodology that had been developed by the scholars of the [[Musaeum|Mouseion]] in Alexandria to the Christian scriptures.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}} The commentaries also display Origen's impressive, encyclopedic knowledge of various subjects{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}} and his ability to cross-reference specific words, listing every place in which a word appears in the scriptures along with all the word's known meanings,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}} a feat made all the more impressive by the fact that he did this in a time when [[Bible concordance]]s had not yet been invented.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}} Origen's massive ''Commentary on the Gospel of John'', which spanned more than thirty-two volumes once it was completed,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=29–30}} was written with the specific intention to not only expound the correct interpretation of the scriptures, but also to refute the interpretations of the Valentinian Gnostic teacher [[Heracleon]],{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}}<ref>Joel C. Elowsky (editor), ''John 1-10. Ancient Christian Commentary on Scripture: New Testament, Voliume 4a.'', page xix, (InterVarsity Press Academic, 2007). {{ISBN|978-0-8308-1489-3}}</ref> who had used the Gospel of John to support his argument that there were really two gods, not one.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=29}} Of the original thirty-two books in the ''Commentary on John'', only nine have been preserved: Books I, II, X, XIII, XX, XXVIII, XXXII, and a fragment of XIX.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}}

Of the original twenty-five books in Origen's ''Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew'', only eight have survived in the original Greek (Books 10-17), covering Matthew 13.36-22.33.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}} An anonymous Latin translation beginning at the point corresponding to Book 12, Chapter 9 or the Greek text and covering Matthew 16.13-27.66 has also survived.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}}{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=124}} The translation contains parts that are not found in the original Greek and is missing parts that are found in it.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}} Origen's ''Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew'' was universally regarded as a classic, even after his condemnation,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}} and it ultimately became the work which established the Gospel of Matthew as the primary gospel.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}} Origen's ''Commentary on the Epistle to the Romans'' was originally fifteen books long, but only tiny fragments of it have survived in the original Greek.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=30}} An abbreviated Latin translation in ten books produced by the monk [[Tyrannius Rufinus]] at the end of the fourth century.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}}{{efn|When Rufinus translated the commentary in the early fifth century he noted in his preface that some of the books were lost, and doubted his ability to 'supply' what was missing and to 'restore' the work's continuity. He also noted his intention to 'abbreviate' the work. Rufinus' abbreviated Latin version in ten books is extant. The Greek fragments were found in papyri at Tura in 1941, and contain Greek excerpts from books 5-6 of the commentary. Comparison of these fragments with Rufinus' translation led to a generally positive evaluation of Rufinus' work. {{harvnb|Heine|2004|page=124}}}} The historian [[Socrates of Constantinople|Socrates Scholasticus]] records that Origen had included an extensive discussion of the application of the title ''[[theotokos]]'' to the Virgin Mary in his commentary,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} but this discussion is not found in Rufinus's translation,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} probably because Rufinus did not approve of Origen's position on the matter, whatever that might have been.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}}

Origen also composed a ''Commentary on the Song of Songs'',{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} in which he took explicit care to explain why the Song of Songs was relevant to a Christian audience.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} The ''Commentary on the Song of Songs'' was Origen's most celebrated commentary{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} and Jerome famously writes in his preface to his translation of two of Origen's homilies over the Song of Songs that "In his other works, Origen habitually excels others. In this commentary, he excelled himself."{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} Origen expanded on the exegesis of the Jewish [[Rabbi Akiva]],{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} interpreting the Song of Songs as a mystical allegory in which the bridegroom represents the Logos and the bride represents the soul of the believer.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} This was the first Christian commentary to expound such an interpretation{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} and it became extremely influential on later interpretations of the Song of Songs.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}} Despite this, the commentary now only survives in part through a Latin translation of it made by Tyrannius Rufinus in the year 410.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=31}}{{efn|Books 1-3, and the beginning of the Book 4, survive, covering Song of Songs 1.1-2.15. Besides not including the later books of the commentary, Rufinus also omitted all of Origen's more technical discussions of the text. {{harvnb|Heine|2004|page=123}}}} Fragments of some other commentaries survive. Citations in Origen's ''[[Philokalia (Origen)|Philokalia]]'' include fragments of the third book of the commentary on Genesis. There is also Ps. i, iv.1, the small commentary on Canticles, and the second book of the large commentary on the same, the twentieth book of the commentary on Ezekiel,{{efn|Codex Vaticanus 1215 gives the division of the twenty-five books of the commentary on Ezekiel, and part of the arrangement of the commentary on Isaiah (beginnings of books VI, VIII, XVI; book X extends from Isa. viii.1 to ix.7; XI from ix.8, to x.11; XII, from x.12 to x.23; XIII from x.24 to xi.9; XIV from xi.10 to xii.6; XV from xiii.1 to xiii.16; XXI from xix.1 to xix.17; XXII from xix.18 to xx.6; XXIII from xxi.1 to xxi.17; XXIV from xxii.1 to xxii.25; XXV from xxiii.1 to xxiii.18; XXVI from xxiv.1 to xxv.12; XXVII from xxvi.1 to xxvi.15; XXVIII from xxvi.16 to xxvii.11a; XXIX from xxvii.11b to xxviii.29; and XXX treats of xxix.1 sqq.).}} and the commentary on Hosea. Of the non-extant commentaries, there is limited evidence of their arrangement.{{efn|Codex Athous Laura 184 gives the division of the fifteen books of the commentary on Romans (except XI and XII) and of the five books on Galatians, as well as the extent of the commentaries on Philippians and Corinthians (Romans I from 1:1 to 1:7; II from 1:8 to 1:25; III from 1:26 to 2:11; IV from 2:12 to 3:15; V from 3:16 to 3:31; VI from 4:1 to 5:7; VII from 5:8 to 5:16; VIII from 5:17 to 6:15; IX from 6:16 to 8:8; X from 8:9 to 8:39; XIII from 11:13 to 12:15; XIV from 12:16 to 14:10; XV from 14:11 to the end; Galatians I from 1:1 to 2:2; II from 2:3 to 3:4; III from 3:5 to 4:5; IV from 4:6 to 5:5; and V from 5:6 to 6:18; the commentary on Philippians extended to 4:1; and on Ephesians to 4:13).}}

===''On the First Principles''===
{{main|On the First Principles}}
Origen's ''On the First Principles'' was the first ever systematic exposition of Christian theology.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} He composed it as a young man between the years 220 and 230 while he was still living in Alexandria.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}} Fragments from Books 3.1 and 4.1-3 of Origen's Greek original are preserved in Origen's ''[[Philokalia (Origen)|Philokalia]]''.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}} A few smaller quotations of the original Greek are preserved in Justinian's ''Letter to Mennas''.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}} The vast majority of the text has only survived in a heavily abridged Latin translation produced by Tyrannius Rufinus in 397.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}} ''On the First Principles'' begins with an essay explaining the nature of theology.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}} Book One describes the heavenly world,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} and includes descriptions of the oneness of God, the relationship between the three persons of the Trinity, the nature of the divine spirit, reason, and angels.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=36–37}} Book Two describes the world of man, including the incarnation of the Logos, the soul, free will, and eschatology.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=37}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} Book Three deals with cosmology, sin, and redemption.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=37}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} Book Four deals with teleology and the interpretation of the scriptures.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=37}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}}

===''Against Celsus''===
{{main|Contra Celsum}}
[[File:Grec 945 48r.jpg|thumb|Greek text of Origen's apologetic treatise ''[[Contra Celsum]]'', which is considered to be the most important work of early Christian apologetics{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=101, 103}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=32–34}}]]

''Against Celsus'' (Greek: Κατὰ Κέλσου; Latin: ''Contra Celsum''), preserved entirely in Greek, was Origen's last treatise, written about 248. It is an apologetic work defending orthodox Christianity against the attacks of the pagan philosopher [[Celsus]], who was seen in the ancient world as early Christianity's foremost opponent.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=32}} In 178, Celsus had written a polemic entitled ''On the True Word'', in which he had made numerous arguments against Christianity.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=32}} The church had responded by ignoring Celsus's attacks,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=32}} but Origen's patron Ambrose brought the matter to his attention.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=32}} Origen initially wanted to ignore Celsus and let his attacks fade,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=32}} but one of Celsus's major claims, which held that no self-respecting philosopher of the Platonic tradition would ever be so stupid as to become a Christian, provoked him to write a rebuttal.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=32}}

In the book, Origen systematically refutes each of Celsus's arguments point-by-point{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=32–34}} and argues for a rational basis of Christian faith.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=103}}{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=127}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=552}} Origen draws heavily on the teachings of Plato{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=102–103}} and argues that Christianity and Greek philosophy are not incompatible,{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=102–103}} and that philosophy contains much that is true and admirable,{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=102–103}} but that the Bible contains far greater wisdom than anything Greek philosophers could ever grasp.{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=102–103}} Origen responds to Celsus's accusation that Jesus had performed his miracles using magic rather than divine powers by asserting that, unlike magicians, Jesus had not performed his miracles for show, but rather to reform his audiences.{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=103}} ''Contra Celsum'' became the most impactful of all early Christian apologetics works;{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=101}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=32–34}} before it was written, Christianity was seen by many as merely a folk religion for the illiterate and uneducated,{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=103}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=32–34}} but Origen raised it to a level of academic respectability.{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=101, 103}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=32–34}} Eusebius admired ''Against Celsus'' so much that, in his ''Against Hierocles'' 1, he declared that ''Against Celsus'' provided an adequate rebuttal to all criticisms the church would ever face.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=33}}

===Other writings===
Between 232–235, while in Caesarea in Palestine, Origen wrote ''On Prayer'', of which the full text has been preserved in the original Greek.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}} After an introduction on the object, necessity, and advantage of [[prayer]], ends with an exegesis of the Lord's Prayer, concluding with remarks on the position, place, and attitude to be assumed during prayer, as well as on the classes of prayer.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=17}} ''On Martyrdom'', or the ''Exhortation to Martyrdom'', also preserved entire in Greek,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} was written some time after the beginning of the persecution of [[Maximinus Thrax|Maximinus]] in the first half of 235.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}} In it, Origen warns against any trifling with idolatry and emphasises the duty of suffering martyrdom manfully; while in the second part he explains the meaning of martyrdom.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=19}}

The papyri discovered at Tura in 1941 contained the Greek texts of two previously unknown works of Origen.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=127}} Neither work can be dated precisely, though both were probably written after the persecution of Maximinus in 235.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=127}} One is ''On the Pascha''.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=127}} The other is ''Dialogue with Heracleides'', a record written by one of Origen's stenographers of a debate between Origen and the Arabian bishop Heracleides, a [[Monarchianism|Quasi-Monarchianist]] who taught that the Father and the Son were the same.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=34–35}}{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=127}}{{sfn|Somos|2015|pages=145–146}}<ref>An English translation of the ''Dialogue'' is in Oulton and Chadwick, eds, ''Alexandrian Christianity'', pp. 430-455.</ref> In the dialogue, Origen uses [[Socratic questioning]] to persuade Heracleides to believe in the "Logos theology",{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=34–35}}{{sfn|Somos|2015|pages=145–149}} the prototypical form of later Trinitarianism.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=35}} The debate between Origen and Heracleides, and Origen's responses in particular, have been noted for their unusually cordial and respectful nature in comparison to the much fiercer polemics of Tertullian or the fourth-century debates between Trinitarians and Arians.{{sfn|Somos|2015|pages=145–149}}

Lost works include two books on the resurrection, written before ''On First Principles'', and also two dialogues on the same theme dedicated to Ambrose. [[Eusebius]] had a collection of more than one hundred letters of Origen,<ref>''Historia ecclesiastica'', VI, xxxvi.3; Eng. transl. ''NPNF'', 2 ser. i.278-279.</ref> and the list of Jerome speaks of several books of his epistles. Except for a few fragments, only three letters have been preserved.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=126}} The first, partly preserved in the Latin translation of Rufinus, is addressed to friends in Alexandria.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=126}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=15}} The second is a short letter to [[Gregory Thaumaturgus]], preserved in the ''Philocalia''.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=126}} The third is an epistle to [[Sextus Julius Africanus]], extant in Greek, replying to a letter from Africanus (also extant), and defending the authenticity of the Greek additions to the book of Daniel.{{sfn|Heine|2004|page=126}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=20}} Forgeries of the writings of Origen made in his lifetime are discussed by Rufinus in ''De adulteratione librorum Origenis''. The ''Dialogus de recta in Deum fide'', the ''[[Philosophumena]]'' attributed to [[Hippolytus of Rome]], and the ''Commentary on Job'' by Julian the Arian have also been ascribed to him.<ref name="Vicchio2006">{{cite book|last=Vicchio|first=Stephen J.|title=Job in the Medieval World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wotLAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA23|date=4 October 2006|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|isbn=978-1-59752-533-6|page=23 n. 2|quote=Origen produced a full-length exposition of the book of Job, as did his student, Avagrius. Fragments of Origen’s commentary survive in ''Migne's Patrologia Graeca'', under the titles, “Selecta of Job” and “Enarrationes in Job.” Another Job commentary attributed to Origen and extant in a Latin translation in three books is not genuine. Early twentieth-century scholars conclusively have attributed the work, ''Commenttarium on Iob'', to Maximinus, a fourth century Arian writer. A third anonymous work on Job preserved in the Migne interprets the book of Job from 1:1 to 3:19. This text also mistakenly has been attributed to Origen. This writer takes the suffering of Job as a symbolic representation of the passion of Christ. He also places the blame for Job’s suffering squarely on the shoulder of Satan, who is seen in the commentary as a demonic figure. Fragments of a smaller work of Job written by Athanasius, Bishop of Alexandria from 328 to 373, also survives in the PG under the title, “Exerpta in Job." Two other selections in Migne, Didymus the Blind's exegesis of Job modeled on Origen’s commentary, and a sermon by Eusebius of Emesa, also attest to the interest in Job on the part of the Christian Alexandrian school.}}</ref><ref name="ScheckErasmus2016">{{cite book|last1=Scheck|first1=Thomas P.|last2=Erasmus|first2=Desiderius|title=Erasmus's Life of Origen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wEONCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA132|date=1 February 2016|publisher=CUA Press|isbn=978-0-8132-2801-3|page=132}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Pseudo-Origen|editor=Carl Heinrich Eduard Lommatzsch|title=Origenis Opera omnia quae graece vel latine tantum exstant et ejus nomine circumferuntur.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P70NAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR2|volume=XVI. Anonymi in Job commentarius. Adamantii de recta in Deum fide|year=1844|publisher=Sumtibus Haude et Spener|quote=Images of [https://books.google.com/books?id=P70NAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR2&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U0kNcOG6gATC3MUF4YqlYFInktGWw Title&nbsp;page&nbsp;i.] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=P70NAAAAYAAJ&pg=PR3&img=1&zoom=3&hl=en&sig=ACfU3U02480n76RFKGzxKAgDcqz-FpUHSw Title&nbsp;page&nbsp;ii.] at [[Google Books]]}}</ref>

==Views==
===Christology===

Origen writes that Jesus was "the firstborn of all creation [who] assumed a body and a human soul."{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=61}} He firmly believed that Jesus had a human soul{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=61}} and abhorred [[Docetism]] (the teaching which held that Jesus had come to earth in spirit form rather than a physical human body).{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=61}} Origen envisioned Jesus's human nature as the one soul that stayed closest to God and remained perfectly faithful to Him, even when all other souls fell away.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=61}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} At Jesus's incarnation, his soul became fused with the Logos and they "intermingled" to become one.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=61–62}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} Thus, according to Origen, Christ was both human and divine,{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=61–62}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} but, like all human souls, Christ's human nature was existent from the beginning.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=62}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}}

Origen was the first to propose the [[ransom theory of atonement]] in its fully developed form,{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}} although [[Irenaeus]] had previously proposed a [[Prototype|prototypical]] form of it.{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}} According to this theory, [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Christ's death on the cross]] was a ransom to Satan in exchange for humanity's liberation.{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}} This theory holds that Satan was tricked by God{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}}{{sfn|Plantinga|Thompson|Lundberg|2010}} because Christ was not only free of sin, but also the incarnate Deity, whom Satan lacked the ability to enslave.{{sfn|Plantinga|Thompson|Lundberg|2010}} The theory was later expanded by theologians such as [[Gregory of Nyssa]] and [[Tyrannius Rufinus|Rufinus of Aquileia]].{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}} In the eleventh century, [[Anselm of Canterbury]] criticized the ransom theory, along with the associated [[Christus Victor]] theory,{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}} resulting in the theory's decline in western Europe.{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}} The theory has nonetheless retained some of its popularity in the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]].{{sfn|Eddy|Beilby|2008|page=86}}

===Cosmology and eschatology===
[[File:Jan_Brueghel_de_Oude_en_Peter_Paul_Rubens_-_Het_aards_paradijs_met_de_zondeval_van_Adam_en_Eva.jpg|thumb|upright=1.7|''[[The Garden of Eden with the Fall of Man]]'' ({{circa}} 1617) by [[Peter Paul Rubens]] and [[Jan Brueghel the Elder]]. Origen based his teaching of the preexistence of souls on an allegorical interpretation of the creation story in the [[Book of Genesis]].{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=53–55}}]]

One of Origen's main teachings was the doctrine of the [[pre-existence|preexistence of souls]],{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=53–55}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} which held that before God created the material world he created a vast number of incorporeal "[[Soul|spiritual intelligences]]" (ψυχαί).{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=53–55}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} All of these souls were at first devoted to the contemplation and love of their Creator,{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} but, as the fervor of the divine fire cooled, almost all of these intelligences eventually grew bored of contemplating God, and their love for him "cooled off" (ψύχεσθαι).{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=53–55}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} When God created the world, the souls which had previously existed without bodies became incarnate.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=53–55}} Those whose love for God diminished the most became [[demons]].{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} Those whose love diminished moderately became human souls, eventually to be incarnated in fleshly bodies.{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} Those whose love diminished the least became [[angels]].{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} One soul, however, who remained perfectly devoted to God became, through love, one with the Word ([[Logos (Christianity)|Logos]]) of God.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=61}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} The Logos eventually took flesh and was born of the [[Virgin Mary]], becoming the [[God-man (Christianity)|God-man]] [[Jesus Christ]].{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=61}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}}

Origen may or may not have believed in the Platonic teaching of ''[[metempsychosis]]'' ("the transmigration of souls"; i.e. [[reincarnation]]).{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=56–57}} He explicitly rejects "the false doctrine of the transmigration of souls into bodies",{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=55}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}} but this may refer only to a specific kind of transmigration.{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=55}} Geddes MacGregor has argued that Origen must have believed in ''metempsychosis'' because it makes sense within his eschatology{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=54–55}} and is never explicitly denied in the Bible.{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=54–55}} Roger E. Olson, however, dismisses the view that Origen believed in reincarnation as a [[New Age]] misunderstanding of Origen's teachings.{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=99–100}} It is certain that Origen rejected the [[Stoicism|Stoic]] notion of a [[Cyclic model|cyclical universe]],{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=55}} which is directly contrary to his eschatology.{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=55}}

Origen believed that, eventually, the whole world would be converted to Christianity,{{sfn|Cahill|1994|page=53}} "since the world is continually gaining possession of more souls."{{sfn|Cahill|1994|pages=53–54}} He believed that the [[Kingdom of Heaven (Gospel of Matthew)|Kingdom of Heaven]] was not yet come,{{sfn|Cahill|1994|page=54}} but that it was the duty of every Christian to make the eschatological reality of the kingdom present in their lives.{{sfn|Cahill|1994|page=54}} Origen was a [[Universalism|Universalist]],{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=56}} who suggested that all people might eventually attain salvation,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=96}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=56}} but only after being purged of their sins through "divine fire".{{sfn|Moore|2005|page=96}} This, of course, in line of Origen's allegorical interpretation, was not ''literal'' fire, but rather the inner anguish of knowing one's own sins.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=96}}{{sfn|Moore|2005|page=96}} Origen was also careful to always maintain that universal salvation was merely a possibility and not a definitive doctrine.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=96}} Jerome quotes Origen as having allegedly written that "after aeons and the one restoration of all things, the state of [[Gabriel]] will be the same as that of the Devil, Paul's as that of [[Caiaphas]], that of virgins as that of prostitutes."{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=56}} Jerome, however, was not above deliberately altering quotations to make Origen seem more like a heretic{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} and Origen himself expressly stated in his ''Letter to Friends in Alexandria'' that Satan and his demons would be not included in the final salvation.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=96}}{{sfn|Kelly|2006|page=199}}

===Ethics===
[[File:Master of Jean de Mandeville The Birth of Esau and Jacob.jpg|thumb|left|''The Birth of Esau and Jacob'' ({{circa}} 1360–1370) by Master of Jean de Mandeville. Origen used the Biblical story of Esau and Jacob to support his theory that a soul's free will actions committed before incarnation determine the conditions of the person's birth.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=58–59}}]]

Origen was an ardent believer in [[free will]]{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=56–59}} and he adamantly rejected the Valentinian idea of [[Election (Christianity)|election]].{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=58}} Instead, Origen believed that even disembodied souls have the power to make their own decisions.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=58}} Furthermore, in his interpretation of the story of [[Jacob]] and [[Esau]], Origen argued that the condition into which a person is born is actually dependent upon what their souls did in this [[Pre-existence|pre-existent]] state.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=58–59}} According to Origen, the superficial unfairness of a person's condition at birth&mdash;with some humans being poor, others rich, some being sick, and others healthy&mdash;is actually a by-product of what the person's soul had done in the pre-existent state.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=58–59}} Origen defends free will in his interpretations of instances of [[Prophecy|divine foreknowledge]] in the scriptures,{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=79}} arguing that Jesus's knowledge of Judas's future betrayal in the gospels and God's knowledge of Israel's future disobedience in the [[Deuteronomistic History]] only show that God knew these events would happen in advance.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=79}} Origen therefore concludes that the individuals involved in these incidents still made their decisions out of their own free will.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=79}}

Origen was an ardent [[Christian pacifism|pacifist]]{{sfn|Caspary|1979|pages=125–127}}{{sfn|Brock|1972|pages=11–12}}{{sfn|Cahill|1994|pages=53–54}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=235–236}} and, in his ''Against Celsus'', he argued that Christianity's inherent pacifism was one of the most outwardly noticeable aspects of the religion.{{sfn|Caspary|1979|pages=125–127}} While Origen did admit that some Christians served in the Roman army,{{sfn|Charles|2005|page=36}}{{sfn|Caspary|1979|pages=126–127}}{{sfn|Cahill|1994|pages=53–54}} he pointed out that most did not{{sfn|Charles|2005|page=36}}{{sfn|Cahill|1994|pages=53–54}} and insisted that engaging in earthly wars was against the way of Christ.{{sfn|Charles|2005|page=36}}{{sfn|Brock|1972|pages=11–12}}{{sfn|Cahill|1994|pages=53–54}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=235–236}} Origen accepted that it was sometimes necessary for a non-Christian state to wage wars,{{sfn|Brock|1972|page=12}} but insisted that it was impossible for a Christian to fight in such a war without compromising his or her faith, since Christ had absolutely forbidden violence of any kind.{{sfn|Brock|1972|page=12}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=235–236}} Origen explained the violence found in certain passages of the Old Testament as allegorical{{sfn|Cahill|1994|page=53}} and pointed out Old Testament passages which he interpreted as supporting nonviolence, such as {{bibleverse|Psalm|7:4-6|HE}} and {{bibleverse|Lamentations|3:27-29|HE}}.{{sfn|Cahill|1994|page=53}} Origen maintained that, if everyone were peaceful and loving like Christians, then there would be no wars and the Empire would not need a military.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=236}}

===Hermeneutics===
{{rquote|right|For who that has understanding will suppose that the first, and second, and third day, and the evening and the morning, existed without a sun, and moon, and stars? And that the first day was, as it were, also without a sky? And who is so foolish as to suppose that God, after the manner of a husbandman, planted a paradise in Eden, towards the east, and placed in it a tree of life, visible and palpable, so that one tasting of the fruit by the bodily teeth obtained life? And again, that one was a partaker of good and evil by masticating what was taken from the tree? And if God is said to walk in the paradise in the evening, and Adam to hide himself under a tree, I do not suppose that anyone doubts that these things figuratively indicate certain mysteries, the history having taken place in appearance, and not literally.|Origen, ''On the First Principles'' [http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/04124.htm IV.16]}}

Origen bases every part of his theology on the Christian scriptures{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=55–58}}{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=56–57}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|page=155}} and never appeals to Platonic teachings without having first supported his argument with a firm scriptural basis.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=58–60}} He saw the scriptures as divinely inspired{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=55–56}}{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=55–58}}{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=56–57}}{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|pages=87–88}} and was also very cautious to never contradict his own interpretation of what was written in them.{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|pages=56–57}} Nonetheless, Origen did have a penchant for speculating beyond what was explicitly stated in the Bible,{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=99–100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=13–17}} and this habit frequently placed him in the hazy realm between strict orthodoxy and heresy.{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=99–100}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=13–17}}

According to Origen, there are two kinds of Biblical literature, which are found in both the Old and New Testaments: ''historia'' ("history, or narrative") and ''nomothesia'' ("legislation or ethical prescription").{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|pages=87–88}} Origen expressly states that the Old and New Testaments should be read together and according to the same rules.{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=88}} Origen further taught that there were three different ways in which passages of scripture could be interpreted.{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=88}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} The "flesh" was the literal, historical interpretation of the passage;{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=88}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} the "soul" was the moral message behind the passage;{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=88}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} and the "spirit" was the eternal, incorporeal reality that the passage conveyed.{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=88}}{{sfn|Grant|1967|page=551}} In Origen's exegesis, the [[Book of Proverbs]], [[Ecclesiastes]], and the [[Song of Songs]] represent perfect examples of the bodily, soulful, and spiritual components of scripture respectively.{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=90}}

Origen saw the "spiritual" interpretation as the deepest and most important meaning of the text{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=90}} and taught that some passages held no literal meaning at all and that their meanings were ''purely'' [[Allegory|allegorical]].{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=90}} Nonetheless, he stressed that "the passages which are historically true are far more numerous than those which are composed with purely spiritual meanings."{{sfn|Ludlow|2013|page=90}} Origen noticed that the accounts of Jesus's life in the four canonical gospels contain irreconcilable contradictions,{{sfn|Perkins|2007|page=292}}{{sfn|Kugel|Greer|1986|page=183}}{{sfn|Keefer|2006|pages=75–76}} but he argued that these contradictions did not undermine the spiritual meanings of the passages in question.{{sfn|Kugel|Greer|1986|page=183}}{{sfn|Keefer|2006|pages=75–76}} Origen's idea of a twofold creation was based on an allegorical interpretation of the creation story found in the first two chapters of the [[Book of Genesis]].{{sfn|Scott|2012|pages=53–55}} The first creation, described in {{bibleverse||Genesis|1:26|9}}, was the creation of the primeval spirits,{{sfn|Layton|2004|page=86}} who are made "in the image of God" and are therefore incorporeal like Him;{{sfn|Layton|2004|page=86}} the second creation described in {{bibleverse||Genesis|2:7|9}} is when the human souls are given ethereal, spiritual bodies{{sfn|Layton|2004|pages=86–87}} and the description in {{bibleverse||Genesis|3:21|9}} of God clothing Adam and Eve in "tunics of skin" refers to the transformation of these spiritual bodies into corporeal ones.{{sfn|Layton|2004|page=86}} Thus, each phase represents a degradation from the original state of incorporeal holiness.{{sfn|Layton|2004|page=86}}

===Theology===
[[File:Shield-Trinity-Scutum-Fidei-English.svg|thumb|Origen significantly contributed to the development of the concept of the [[Trinity]]{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=24}}{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=37}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|pages=154–156}} and was among the first to name the Holy Spirit as a member of the Godhead,{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}} but he was also a [[Subordinationism|Subordinationist]],{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=38}}{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}}{{sfn|Pollard|1970|page=95}}{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=161}} who taught that the Father was superior to the Son and the Son was superior to the Holy Spirit.{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=38}}{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}}{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=161}}]]

Origen's conception of God the Father is [[Apophatic theology|apophatic]]—a perfect unity, invisible and incorporeal, transcending all things material, and therefore inconceivable and incomprehensible. He is likewise unchangeable and transcends space and time. But his power is limited by his goodness, justice, and wisdom; and, though entirely free from necessity, his goodness and omnipotence constrained him to reveal himself. This revelation, the external self-emanation of God, is expressed by Origen in various ways, the Logos being only one of many. The revelation was the first creation of God (cf. Prov. viii. 22), in order to afford creative mediation between God and the world, such mediation being necessary, because God, as changeless unity, could not be the source of a multitudinous creation.

The Logos is the rational creative principle that permeates the universe.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=80}} The Logos acts on all human beings through their capacity for logic and rational thought,{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=79–80}} guiding them to the truth of God's revelation.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=79–80}} As they progress in their rational thinking, all humans become more and more like Christ.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=80}} Nonetheless, they retain their individuality and do not become subsumed into Christ.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=80–81}} Creation came into existence only through the Logos, and God's nearest approach to the world is the command to create. While the Logos is substantially a unity, he comprehends a multiplicity of concepts, so that Origen terms him, in Platonic fashion, "essence of essences" and "idea of ideas".

Origen significantly contributed to the development of the idea of the [[Trinity]].{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=24}}{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=37}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|pages=154–156}} He declared the Holy Spirit to be a part of the Godhead{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}} and interpreted the [[Parable of the Lost Coin]] to mean that the Holy Spirit dwells within each and every person{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=159–160}} and that the inspiration of the Holy Spirit was necessary for any kind of speech dealing with God.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=160}} Origen taught that the activity of all three parts of the Trinity were necessary for a person to attain salvation.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=161}} In one fragment preserved by Rufinus in his Latin translation of [[Pamphilus of Caesarea|Pamphilus]]'s ''Defense of Origen'', Origen seems to apply the phrase ''homooúsios'' (ὁμοούσιος; "of the same substance") to the relationship between the Father and the Son,{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=38}}{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=132}} but in other passages, Origen rejected the belief that the Son and the Father were one ''hypostasis'' as heretical.{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=132}} According to [[Rowan Williams]], because the words ''ousia'' and ''hypostasis'' were used synonymously in Origen's time,{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=132}} Origen almost certainly would have rejected ''homoousios'' as heretical.{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=132}} Williams states that it is impossible to verify whether the quote that uses the word ''homoousios'' really comes from Pamphilus at all, let alone Origen.{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=132}}

Nonetheless, Origen was a [[Subordinationism|Subordinationist]],{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=38}}{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}}{{sfn|Pollard|1970|page=95}}{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=161}} meaning he believed that the Father was superior to the Son and the Son was superior to the Holy Spirit,{{sfn|La Due|2003|page=38}}{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}}{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=161}} a model based on Platonic [[Proportionality (mathematics)|proportions]].{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}} Jerome records that Origen had written that God the Father is invisible to all beings, including even the Son and the Holy Spirit,{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=152–153}} and that the Son is invisible to the Holy Spirit as well.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=152–153}} At one point Origen suggests that the Son was created by the Father and that the Holy Spirit was created by the Son,{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=153}} but, at another point, he writes that "Up to the present I have been able to find no passage in the Scriptures that the Holy Spirit is a created being."{{sfn|Olson|Hall|2002|page=25}}{{sfn|Greggs|2009|page=154}} At the time when Origen was alive, orthodox views on the Trinity had not yet been formulated{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=152–153}}{{sfn|Badcock|1997|page=43}} and Subordinationism was not yet considered heretical.{{sfn|Greggs|2009|pages=152–153}}{{sfn|Badcock|1997|page=43}} In fact, virtually all orthodox theologians prior to the [[Arian controversy]] in the latter half of the fourth century were Subordinationists to some extent.{{sfn|Badcock|1997|page=43}} Origen's Subordinationism may have developed out of his efforts to defend the unity of God against the Gnostics.{{sfn|Pollard|1970|page=95}}

==Influence on the later church==
[[File:First Council of Nicea by V.Surikov (1876-7, GTG).jpg|thumb|[[Athanasius of Alexandria]], shown standing in this 1876 oil painting by [[Vasily Surikov]], was deeply influenced by Origen's teachings.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=249–250}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}]]
===Before the crises===
Origen is often seen as the first major Christian theologian.{{sfn|Moore|2014}} Though his orthodoxy had been questioned in Alexandria while he was alive,{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=13–17}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} Origen's torture during the Decian persecution led [[Pope Dionysius of Alexandria]] to rehabilitate Origen's memory there, hailing him as a martyr for the faith.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=22}} Later, after Origen's death, Dionysius became one of the foremost proponents of Origen's theology.{{sfn|Rusch|1980|pages=15–16}}{{sfn|Chadwick|1993|page=114}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=246}} Every Christian theologian who came after him was influenced by his theology, whether directly or indirectly.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} Origen's contributions to theology were so vast and complex, however, that his followers frequently emphasized drastically different parts of his teachings to the expense of other parts.{{sfn|Rusch|1980|pages=15–16}}{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=162}} Dionysius emphasized Origen's Subordinationist views,{{sfn|Rusch|1980|pages=15–16}}{{sfn|Chadwick|1993|page=114}} which led him to deny the unity of the Trinity, causing controversy throughout North Africa.{{sfn|Rusch|1980|pages=15–16}}{{sfn|Chadwick|1993|page=114}} At the same time, Origen's other disciple [[Theognostus of Alexandria]] taught that the Father and the Son were "of one substance".{{sfn|Rusch|1980|page=15}}

For centuries after his death, Origen was regarded as the bastion of orthodoxy{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=99}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|pages=155–156}} and his philosophy practically defined Eastern Christianity.{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=99–100}} Origen himself was revered as one of the greatest of all Christian teachers;{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=25}} he was especially beloved by monks, who saw themselves as continuing in Origen's ascetic legacy.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=25}} As time progressed, however, Origen became criticized under the standard of orthodoxy in later eras, rather than the standards of his own lifetime.{{sfn|Harding|2004|pages=162–163}} In the early fourth century, the Christian writer [[Methodius of Olympus]] criticized some of Origen's more speculative arguments,{{sfn|Ramelli|2013|page=262}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=163}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=247}} but otherwise agreed with Origen on all other points of theology.{{sfn|Ramelli|2013|pages=262–263}} Peter of Antioch and [[Eustathius of Antioch]] also criticized Origen as heretical.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=163}}

Both orthodox and heterodox theologians claimed to be following in the tradition Origen had established.{{sfn|Olson|1999|pages=99–100}} [[Athanasius of Alexandria]], the most prominent supporter of the [[Holy Trinity]] at the [[First Council of Nicaea]], was deeply influenced by Origen{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=249–250}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} and so were [[Basil of Caesarea]], [[Gregory of Nyssa]], and [[Gregory of Nazianzus]] (the so-called "[[Cappadocian Fathers]]").{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=249}}{{sfn|Olson|1999|page=100}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} At the same time, however, many commonalities exist between Origen's theology and [[Arianism]].{{sfn|Williams|2001|pages=131–134}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=249–250}} Although the relationship between the two is still disputed,{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=131}} in antiquity, many orthodox Christians believed that Origen was the true and ultimate source of the Arian heresy.{{sfn|Williams|2001|page=131}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=249–251}}

===First Origenist Crisis===
{{main|Origenist Crises}}
[[File:Domenico Ghirlandaio - St Jerome in his study.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|''[[St Jerome in His Study (Ghirlandaio)|St. Jerome in His Study]]'' (1480), by [[Domenico Ghirlandaio]]. Although initially a student of Origen's teachings, [[Jerome]] turned against him during the First Origenist Crisis.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=252–253}} He nonetheless remained influenced by Origen's teachings for his entire life.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=253}}]]

The first Origenist crisis began in the late fourth century AD, coinciding with the beginning of monasticism in Palestine.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=163}} The first stirring of the controversy came from the [[Cyprus|Cyprian]] bishop [[Epiphanius of Salamis]], who was determined to root out all heresies and refute them.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=163}} Epiphanius attacked Origen in his anti-heretical treatises ''Ancoratus'' (375) and ''[[Panarion]]'' (376), compiling a list of teachings Origen had espoused that Epiphanius regarded as heretical.{{sfn|Harding|2004|pages=163–164}}{{sfn|Kim|2015|page=19}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=249–250}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} Epiphanius's treatises portray Origen as an originally orthodox Christian who had been corrupted and turned into a heretic by the evils of "Greek education".{{sfn|Kim|2015|page=19}} Epiphanius particularly objected to Origen's Subordinationism, his "excessive" use of allegorical hermeneutic, and his habit of proposing ideas about the Bible "speculatively, as exercises" rather than "dogmatically".{{sfn|Harding|2004|pages=163–164}}

Epiphanius asked [[John II, Bishop of Jerusalem|John, the bishop of Jerusalem]] to condemn Origen as a heretic. John refused on the grounds that a person could not be retroactively condemned as a heretic after the person had already died.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} In 393, a monk named Atarbius advanced a petition to have Origen and his writings to be censured.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} [[Tyrannius Rufinus]], a priest at the monastery on the [[Mount of Olives]] who had been ordained by John of Jerusalem and was a longtime admirer of Origen, rejected the petition outright.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=252}} Rufinus's close friend and associate [[Jerome]], who had also studied Origen, however, came to agree with the petition.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=252}} Around the same time, [[John Cassian]], a [[Semipelagianism|Semipelagian]] monk, introduced Origen's teachings to the West.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=248–249}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}

In 394, Epiphanius wrote to John of Jerusalem, again asking for Origen to be condemned, insisting that Origen's writings denigrated human sexual reproduction and accusing him of having been an [[Encratites|Encratite]].{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} John once again denied this request.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} By 395, Jerome had allied himself with the anti-Origenists and begged John of Jerusalem to condemn Origen, a plea which John once again refused.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} Epiphanius launched a campaign against John, openly preaching that John was an Origenist deviant.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} He successfully persuaded Jerome to break communion with John and ordained Jerome's brother Paulinianus as a priest in defiance of John's authority.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}

Meanwhile, in 397, Rufinus published a Latin translation of Origen's ''On First Principles''.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Heine|2010|page=125}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=252–253}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}} Rufinus was convinced that Origen's original treatise had been interpolated by heretics and that these interpolations were the source of the heterodox teachings found in it.{{sfn|Heine|2010|page=125}} He therefore heavily modified Origen's text, omitting and altering any parts which disagreed with contemporary Christian orthodoxy.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}}{{sfn|Heine|2010|page=125}} In the introduction to this translation, Rufinus mentioned that Jerome had studied under Origen's disciple [[Didymus the Blind]], implying that Jerome was a follower of Origen.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=252}} Jerome was so incensed by this that he resolved to produce his own Latin translation of ''On the First Principles'', in which he promised to translate every word exactly as it was written and lay bare Origen's heresies to the whole world.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}}{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|pages=252–253}} Jerome's translation has been lost in its entirety.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=36}}

In 399, the Origenist crisis reached Egypt.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} [[Pope Theophilus of Alexandria]] was sympathetic to the supporters of Origen{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=164}} and the church historian, [[Sozomen]], records that he had openly preached the Origenist teaching that God was incorporeal.{{sfn|Wessel|2004|page=24}} In his ''Festal Letter'' of 399, he denounced those who believed that God had a literal, human-like body, calling them illiterate "simple ones".{{sfn|Wessel|2004|page=24}}{{sfn|Harding|2004|pages=164–165}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=253}} A large mob of Alexandrian monks who regarded God as anthropomorphic rioted in the streets.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} According to the church historian [[Socrates Scholasticus]], in order to prevent a riot, Theophilus made a sudden about-face and began denouncing Origen.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=253}} In the year 400, Theophilus summoned a council in Alexandria, which condemned Origen and all his followers as heretics for having taught that God was incorporeal, which they decreed contradicted the only true and orthodox position, which was that God had a literal, physical body resembling that of a human.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}}{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=57}}{{sfn|Wessel|2004|pages=24–25}}{{efn|[[Socrates Scholasticus]] describes this condemnation as a deception to gain the confidence of the Alexandrian monastic community, which vehemently upheld the teaching of an anthropomorphic Deity.{{sfn|Wessel|2004|page=24}}}}

Theophilus labelled Origen himself as the "hydra of all heresies"{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=57}} and persuaded [[Pope Anastasius I]] to sign the letter of the council, which primarily denounced the teachings of the [[Nitria (monastic site)|Nitrian monks]] associated with [[Evagrius Ponticus]].{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} In 402, Theophilus expelled Origenist monks from Egyptian monasteries and banished the four monks known as the "[[Tall Brothers]]", who were leaders of the Nitrian community.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=253}} [[John Chrysostom]], the [[Ecumenical Patriarch of Constantinople|Patriarch of Constantinople]], granted the Tall Brothers asylum, a fact which Theophilus used to orchestrate John's condemnation and removal from his position at the [[Synod of the Oak]] in July of 403.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}}{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=253}} Once John Chrysostom had been deposed, Theophilus restored normal relations with the Origenist monks in Egypt and the first Origenist crisis came to an end.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}}

===Second Origenist Crisis===
{{main|Origenist Crises}}
[[File:Mosaic of Justinianus I - Basilica San Vitale (Ravenna).jpg|thumb|The Emperor [[Justinian I]], shown here in a contemporary mosaic portrait from [[Ravenna]], denounced Origen as a heretic{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} and ordered all of his writings to be burned.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}]]

The Second Origenist Crisis occurred in the sixth century, during the height of [[Eastern Christian monasticism#Byzantine monasticism|Byzantine monasticism]].{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} Although the Second Origenist Crisis is not nearly as well documented as the first,{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} it seems to have primarily concerned the teachings of Origen's later followers, rather than anything Origen himself had actually written.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} Origen's disciple Evagrius Ponticus had advocated [[Christian contemplation#Contemplative prayer|contemplative, noetic prayer]],{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} but other monastic communities prioritized asceticism in prayer, emphasizing fasting, labors, and vigils.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} Some Origenist monks in Palestine, referred to by their enemies as "Isochristoi" (meaning "those who would assume equality with Christ"), emphasized Origen's teaching of the pre-existence of souls and held that all souls were originally equal to Christ's and would become equal again at the end of time.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=165}} Another faction of Origenists in the same region instead insisted that Christ was the "leader of many brethren", as the first-created being.{{sfn|Harding|2004|pages=165–166}} This faction was more moderate and they were referred to by their opponents as "Protoktistoi" ("First Createds").{{sfn|Harding|2004|pages=165–166}} Both factions accused the other of heresy and other Christians accused both of them of heresy.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}}

The Protoktistoi appealed to the Emperor [[Justinian I]] to condemn the Isochristoi of heresy through Pelagius, the papal ''[[apocrisarius]]''.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} In 543 AD, Pelagius presented Justinian with documents, including a letter denouncing Origen written by Patriarch [[Ecumenical Patriarch Mennas of Constantinople|Mennas of Constantinople]],<ref name="Origen and Origenism"/><ref>[http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/encyc01.html?term=apocatastasis Apocatastasis{{snd}} §2. Opponents] in New Schaff-Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge, Vol_ I, Aachen{{snd}} Basilians at Christian Classics Ethereal Library</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Origenes der Diamantene |last=Sträuli |first=Robert | year=1987 | publisher = ABZ Verlag | location = Zurich | isbn = 3-85516-005-8 | pages = 71, 355–357 }}</ref>{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} along with excerpts from Origen's ''On First Principles'' and several anathemata against Origen.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} A [[Synod of Constantinople (543)|domestic synod convened to address the issue]] concluded that the Isochristoi's teachings were heretical and, seeing Origen as the ultimate culprit behind the heresy, denounced Origen himself as a heretic as well.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} Emperor Justinian ordered for all of Origen's writings to be burned.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26}}{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} In the west, the ''[[Decretum Gelasianum]]'', which was written sometime between 519 and 553, listed Origen as an author whose writings were to be categorically banned.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}}

In 553, during the early days of the [[Second Council of Constantinople]] (the Fifth Ecumenical Council), when [[Pope Vigilius]] was still refusing to take part in it, despite Justinian holding him hostage, the bishops at the council ratified an open letter which condemned Origen as the leader of the Isochristoi.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} The letter was not part of the official acts of the council and it more or less repeated the edict issued by the Synod of Constantinople in 543.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} It cites objectionable writings attributed to Origen, but all the writings referred to in it were actually written by Evagrius Ponticus.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} After the council officially opened, but while Pope Vigillius was still refusing to take part, Justinian presented the bishops with the problem of a text known as ''[[Three-Chapter Controversy|The Three Chapters]]'', which attacked the Antiochene Christology.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}}

The bishops drew up a list of anathemata against the heretical teachings contained within ''The Three Chapters'' and those associated with them.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} In the official text of the eleventh anathema, Origen is condemned as a Christological heretic,{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}}{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} but Origen's name does not appear at all in the ''Homonoia'', the first draft of the anathemata issued by the imperial [[Chancery (medieval office)|chancery]],{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} nor does it appear in the version of the conciliar proceedings that was eventually signed by Pope Vigillius, a long time afterwards.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} These discrepancies may indicate that Origen's name may have been retrospectively inserted into the text after the Council.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}} Some authorities believe these anathemata belong to an earlier local synod.<ref>{{Cite book|first=Rowan A. |last=Greer |title=Origen |publisher=Paulist Press |location=[[New York City]] |year=1979 |page=3 |isbn=0-8091-2198-0}}</ref> Even if Origen's name did appear in the original text of the anathema, the teachings attributed to Origen that are condemned in the anathema were actually the ideas of later Origenists, which had very little grounding in anything Origen himself had actually written.{{sfn|Harding|2004|page=166}}<ref name="Origen and Origenism"/>{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=57}} In fact, Popes Vigilius (537–555), [[Pope Pelagius I|Pelagius I]] (556–61), [[Pope Pelagius II|Pelagius II]] (579–90), and [[Pope Gregory I|Gregory the Great]] (590–604) were only aware that the Fifth Council specifically dealt with ''The Three Chapters'' and make no mention of Origenism or Universalism, nor spoke as if they knew of its condemnation&mdash;even though Gregory the Great was opposed to Universalism.<ref name="Origen and Origenism"/>

===After the anathemas===
{{rquote|right|If orthodoxy were a matter of intention, no theologian could be more orthodox than Origen, none more devoted to the cause of the Christian faith.|[[Henry Chadwick (theologian)|Henry Chadwick]], scholar of early Christianity, in ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]''{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}}}}
As a direct result of the numerous condemnations of his work, only a tiny fraction of Origen's voluminous writings have survived.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|pages=25–26}}{{sfn|Ehrman|2003|pages=155–156}} Nonetheless, these writings still amount to a massive number of Greek and Latin texts, very few of which have yet been translated into English.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=25}} Many more writings have survived in fragments through quotations from later Church Fathers.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} It is likely that the writings containing Origen's most unusual and speculative ideas have been lost to time,{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=56}} making it nearly impossible to determine whether Origen actually held the heretical views which the anathemas against him ascribed to him.{{sfn|MacGregor|1982|page=56}} Nonetheless, in spite of the decrees against Origen, the church remained enamored of him{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} and he remained a central figure of Christian theology throughout the first millennium.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} He continued to be revered as the founder of Biblical exegesis{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}} and anyone in the first millennium who took the interpretation of the scriptures seriously would have had knowledge of Origen's teachings.{{sfn|McGuckin|2004|page=26}}

Jerome's Latin translations of Origen's homilies were widely read in western Europe throughout the Middle Ages{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} and Origen's teachings greatly influenced those of the Byzantine monk [[Maximus the Confessor]] ({{circa}} 550–662) and the Irish theologian [[John Scotus Eriugena]] ({{circa}} 810–877).{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} Since the [[Renaissance]], the debate over Origen's orthodoxy has continued to rage.{{sfn|Chadwick|2017}} [[Basilios Bessarion]] (1403–1472), a Greek refugee who fled to Italy after the [[Fall of Constantinople]] in 1453, produced a Latin translation of Origen's ''Contra Celsum'', which was printed in 1481.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} Major controversy erupted in 1487, after the [[Renaissance humanism|Italian humanist]] scholar [[Giovanni Pico della Mirandola]] (1463–1494) issued a thesis arguing that "it is more reasonable to believe that Origen was saved than he was damned."{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} A papal commission condemned Pico's position on account of the anathemas against Origen, but not until after the debate had received considerable attention.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}}

The most prominent advocate of Origen during the Renaissance was the Dutch humanist scholar [[Desiderius Erasmus]] (1466 – 1536), who regarded Origen as the greatest of all Christian authors{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} and wrote in a letter to [[John Eck]] that he learned more about Christian philosophy from a single page of Origen than from ten pages of Augustine.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} Erasmus especially admired Origen for his lack of rehetorical flourishes, which were so common in the writings of other Patristic authors.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} Erasmus also borrowed heavily from Origen's defense of free will in ''On First Principles'' in his 1524 treatise ''[[De libero arbitrio diatribe sive collatio|On Free Will]]'', now considered his most important theological work.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} In 1527, Erasmus translated and published the portion of Origen's ''Commentary on the Gospel of Matthew'' that survived only in Greek{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}} and, in 1536, he published the most complete edition of Origen's writings that had ever been published at that time.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=255}} While Origen's emphasis on the human effort in attaining salvation appealed to the Renaissance humanists, it made him far less appealing to the proponents of the [[Reformation]].{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}} [[Martin Luther]] (1483–1546) deplored Origen's understanding of salvation as irredeemably defective{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}} and declared "in all of Origen there is not one word about Christ."{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}} Consequently, he ordered for Origen's writings to be banned.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}} Nonetheless, the earlier Czech reformer [[Jan Hus]] ({{circa}} 1369–1415) had taken inspiration from Origen for his view that the church is a spiritual reality rather than an official hierarchy{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}} and Luther's contemporary, the Swiss reformer [[Huldrych Zwingli]] (1484–1531), took inspiration from Origen for his interpretation of the eucharist as symbolic.{{sfn|Trigg|1983|page=256}}

In the seventeenth century, the English [[Cambridge Platonists|Cambridge Platonist]] [[Henry More]] (1614 – 1687) was a devoted Origenist{{sfn|Hutton|2006|page=205}} and, although he did reject the notion of universal salvation,{{sfn|Hutton|2006|page=205}} he accepted most of Origen's other teachings.{{sfn|Hutton|2006|page=205}} [[Pope Benedict XVI]] expressed admiration for Origen,{{sfn|Pope Benedict XVI|2007|pages=24–27}} describing him in a sermon as part of a series on the Church Fathers as "a figure crucial to the whole development of Christian thought", "a true 'maestro'", and "not only a brilliant theologian but also an exemplary witness of the doctrine he passed on".{{sfn|Pope Benedict XVI|2007|page=24}} He concludes the sermon by inviting his audience to "welcome into your hearts the teaching of this great master of the faith".{{sfn|Pope Benedict XVI|2007|page=27}} Modern Protestant evangelicals admire Origen for his passionate devotion to the scriptures,{{sfn|Franke|2003}} but are frequently baffled or even appalled by his allegorical interpretation of them, which many believe ignores the literal, historical truth behind them.{{sfn|Franke|2003}}

