'''Zbigniew Oleśnicki''' ({{IPA-pl|ˈzbʲiɡɲɛf ɔlɛˈɕɲit͡skʲi|lang}}; 5 December 1389 in [[Sienno, Masovian Voivodeship]] &ndash; 1 April 1455), known in [[Latin]] as '''Sbigneus''', was a high-ranking [[Roman Catholic]] clergyman and an influential [[Poland|Polish]] statesman and diplomat. He served as [[Bishop of Kraków]] from 1423 until his death in 1455. He took part in the management of the country's most important affairs, initially as a royal secretary under King [[Władysław II Jagiełło]] and later as the effective [[regent]] during King [[Władysław III of Poland|Władysław III]]'s minority. In 1449 he became the first native Polish [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]].
==Biography== At the age of twenty he was secretary to King [[Władysław Jagiełło]], and fought with him in the [[battle of Grunwald]] on 15 July 1410.<ref name=CE>{{CathEncy|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11240c.htm|title=Zbigniew Olesnicki}}</ref> A favourite with the king, he took part in the management of the country's most important affairs.<ref name=CE/> His influence with the king greatly aided him in opposing the [[Hussites]], who had gained royal favour.<ref name=CE/> On 9 July 1423, he was appointed to the [[episcopal See]] of [[Kraków]], and in 1433 he was sent by the king as legate to the [[council of Basle]], where he endeavoured to be on friendly terms with both parties.<ref name=CE/>
In the 1430s he opposed [[Spytek of Melsztyn]] in a conflict which led to a short lived civil war and Spytek's death in 1439.<ref name="Penson">{{cite book|author1=Oskar Halecki |author2=W: F. Reddaway |author3=J. H. Penson |title=The Cambridge History of Poland|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N883AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA237|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-1-00-128802-4|page=237}}</ref><ref name="Jaques2007">{{cite book|author=Tony Jaques|title=Dictionary of Battles and Sieges: F-O|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dh6jydKXikoC&pg=PA412|year=2007|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33538-9|page=412}}</ref>
On 18 December 1439, he was created [[cardinal priest]] with the titular church of [[St. Prisca]], by [[Pope Eugene IV]].<ref name=CE/> (The antipope [[Felix V]] also made him a cardinal on 20 January 1440.<ref>Konrad Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica medii aevi'', Münster: sumptibus et typis librariae regensbergianae, 1901), p. 9.</ref>). As cardinal, his influence in Poland was second only to that of the king, and, during the frequent absence of [[Casimir IV Jagiellon|Casimir IV]] in [[Lithuania]], he transacted the affairs of the State.<ref name=CE/> [[file:Zbigniew Olesnicki.jpg|left|150px]] He was recognized as one of the two most important Polish magnates of his time (the other one was magnate {{ill|Jan Tęczyński (died 1470)|lt=Jan Tęczyński|pl|Jan z Tęczyna}}).<ref name=pwn>{{pl icon}} [http://encyklopedia.pwn.pl/haslo.php?id=3986965 Tęczyńscy], [[Internetowa encyklopedia PWN|PWN Encyklopedia]]</ref>
In 1449, after the death of [[archbishop of Gniezno]] and [[primate of Poland]] [[Wincenty Kot]], the position was proposed to Oleśnicki, but he refused it. It then passed to his political rival, bishop [[Władysław Oporowski]].<ref name=diec>{{pl icon}} Bernadeta Kruszyk, [http://www.archidiecezja.pl/pl/historia/arcybiskupi/poczet_arcybiskupow_gnieznienskich/wladyslaw_oporowski.html Władysław Oporowski], Poczet Arcybiskupów Gnieźnieńskich, Archidiecezja Gnieźnieńska</ref>
In his conduct of Poland's affairs Oleśnicki entertained far-reaching imperial dreams, which included a complete assimilation of [[Lithuania]] into the Polish state and the conquest of [[Silesia]] from the [[Kingdom of Bohemia]]. In particular, Oleśnicki pursued the idea of a Crusading alliance with [[Hungary]] against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] Turks, with the ultimate aim of extending Poland's boundaries to the [[Black Sea]]. This was manifested in promoting [[Władysław III of Poland|Władysław III]]'s taking the [[King of Hungary|Hungarian Crown]] - to which some Polish magnates were strongly opposed. However, all these aspirations came to naught with King Władysław's death at the [[Battle of Varna]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}
Being a man of great learning, he advanced the study of arts and letters in every possible way, and the flourishing condition of the [[University of Krakow]] during his episcopacy is due chiefly to his efforts.<ref name=CE/> The well-known chronicler [[Jan Długosz]] was his secretary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/05069b.htm|title=Jan Dlugosz|work=[[Catholic Encyclopedia]]}}</ref> To repress the spread of Hussitism he called [[Giovanni da Capistrano]] (then in [[Breslau]]) and the [[Minorites]] to Kraków.<ref name=CE/>
Da Capistrano, whom Oleśnicki invited, was also known for his anti-Jewish zeal, in which he engaged in Poland as in other countries. Oleśnicki's own Anti-[[Jew]]ish intolerance was manifested in his strongly criticising [[Casimir IV Jagiellon|Casimir IV]] for reaffirming in 1453 the tolerant measures towards Jews enacted by [[Casimir III of Poland|Casimir III]]. Under Oleśnicki's influence, the 1454 [[Statutes of Nieszawa]] included the provisions that Jews' rights be "restricted when they contradict [[canon law]]" and that Polish Jews be compelled to wear distinctive clothing. However, this was never enforced in practice.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}
